<xs:schema xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:thesu="http://alchemeast.eu/thesu/ns/1.0"
  elementFormDefault="qualified" targetNamespace="http://alchemeast.eu/thesu/ns/1.0">
  <xs:annotation>
    <xs:appinfo>TheSu XML version 0.93</xs:appinfo>
    <xs:documentation>Welcome to TheSu XML!</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>This is version 0.93 of the Thesu XML Schema Definition and
      documentation.</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>This XML Schema Definition and documentation was entirely authored by Daniele
      Morrone. For queries, suggestions, or feedback regarding this schema, please feel free to
      contact him. Direct your emails to 'dmorroneb', followed by the at symbol, then 'gmail', and,
      finally, add the common email domain suffix.</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>The URL for the TheSu XML Schema Definition is
      https://alchemeast.eu/thesu/ns/1.0/TheSu.xsd. To associate this schema with your XML file,
      start by creating a 'thesu:TheSu' root element. Then, include in this element the following
      attributes: <thesu:TheSu xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://alchemeast.eu/thesu/ns/1.0 https://alchemeast.eu/thesu/ns/1.0/TheSu.xsd" xmlns:thesu="http://alchemeast.eu/thesu/ns/1.0"> </thesu:TheSu>
    </xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>This software was developed as part of two research projects. From 2018 to
      2022, as part of Alchemy in the Making: From Ancient Babylonia via Graeco-Roman Egypt into the
      Byzantine, Syriac, and Arabic Traditions, acronym AlchemEast. The AlchemEast project has
      received funding from the European Research Council (ERC) under the European Union’s Horizon
      2020 research and innovation programme (G.A. 724914). From 2022 to 2023, as part of Not
      Another History of Platonism: The Role of Aristotle’s Criticisms of Plato in the Development
      of Ancient Platonism, acronym PlatoViaAristotle. The PlatoViaAristotle project has received
      funding from the European Research Council (ERC) under the European Union’s Horizon 2020
      research and innovation programme (G.A. 885273).</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>For effective navigation of this documentation, it is advisable to start with
      the 'TheSu' element, the root element of a TheSu document. Following this, attention should be
      directed towards the 'THESIS', 'SUPPORT', and 'PROPOSITION' elements, as they are the most
      significant. It is recommended to explore their attributes, children, and descendant elements
      subsequent to reviewing their respective definitions.</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>Graphical conventions: &#8226; opening and closing apostrophes ['example']
      signal the name of an XML or HTML element; &#8226; opening and closing apostrophes delimiting
      a string starting with the at sign ['@example'] signal the name of an XML attribute; &#8226;
      opening and closing quotation marks ["example"] can signal a. an attribute value, b. a
      freeform interpretation of an attribute value, c. an element as characterized by the value of
      one of its attributes or of one of its prominent descendant elements' attributes (e.g. "base
      edition" as referred to a 'bibliographyRef' whose '@baseEdition' is specified as "true", or
      "argumentative" as referred to a 'SUPPORT' whose descendant 'argumentation' has a '@rank'
      value superior to that of its siblings in the highest ranking 'supportFunctionsGroup'), d. a
      quotation; &#8226; rightwards arrow between two element names ['example' &#8594; 'example']
      signals that the element on the right is a child of the element on the left; &#9702; Note:
      This schema differentiates among the action verbs 'must', 'should', 'may', and 'can', in
      relation to the annotator's tasks. 'Must' indicates both the mandatory elements and attributes
      that are enforced by the XSD rules and those critical features that, while essential for the
      annotation, may not be automatically enforced. Conversely, 'should' is used to recommend best
      practices that are advisable but not obligatory. 'May' and 'can', on the other hand, lean
      towards neutrality, simply indicating available options without a strong recommendation or
      preference.</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>Latest updates: [2023.11.23 Daniele Morrone; v. 0.96] Added human-readable
      definitions to almost all elements and attributes for annotating processual theses. Also made
      extensive fixes, integrations, and redesigns for a more accurate alignment with the intended
      logic. [2022.07.11 Daniele Morrone; v. 0.90] Added elements and attributes for the annotation
      of processual theses. [2022.06.22 Daniele Morrone; v. 0.72] Bug fix and small integrations.
      [2022.05.15 Daniele Morrone; v. 0.72] Corrected typos and spelling mistakes. [2021.12.27
      Daniele Morrone; v. 0.72] Re-modelled the 'proof' complexType on the basis of 'includedRef'
      and re-defined 'marker' elements as restrictions of this complexType only allowing for
      'locusRef'. [2021.12.01 Daniele Morrone] TheSu documentation version 0.70
      completed.</xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>Roadmap to version 1.00: &#10007; Adding all the missing human-readable
      elements' and complexTypes' definitions &#10007; Integrating several planned miscellaneous
      changes and improvements into the scheme &#10007; Re-evaluating the logic of the distinction
      between complexTypes and elements &#10007; Revising all the human-readable definitions to
      refer more generally to "data" in primary sources rather than "text", to structurally allow
      for multimedial TheSu annotations &#10007; Expanding the TheSu documents' metadata (allowing
      to include information on e.g. the annotators who worked on them). </xs:documentation>
    <xs:documentation>Plans for future versions: &#10007; Improving the integration of the TheSu
      documents' metadata with already-existing metadata in different formats (e.g. RDF); &#10007;
      Adding in-code examples to the documentation of each element and attribute in the XSD.
    </xs:documentation>
  </xs:annotation>
