  <xs:complexType name="comparisonDomain">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the quantificational domain of a superlative comparison,
        i.e. the limited reference group in which the superlative sentence is regarded to be true
        (e.g., implicitly, "celestial bodies" in the statement "the sun sends us the most heat").
        This may be specified in three different ways: in the case the reference group corresponds
        to one or more of the keywords annotated for the 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION', by referring to
        them via 'keywordSubRef'; in the case the group corresponds to one or more keywords whose
        tags are present in the "keywordTags" authority record associated to the TheSu corpus, and
        which have not been used to label any of the keywords included in the 'THESIS' or
        'PROPOSITION', by referring to them in one or more 'keywordTagRef' and specifying their
        narrow themes; otherwise, in the case the reference group is hardly associated with any
        specific keyword, by freely designating it in 'microThemedFreeText' as a string, while also
        providing it, if possible, of its own micro-thematic annotation. In the latter two cases, to
        prove that the relevance of the specified quantificational domain, the annotator may use
        'proof' and refer to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding
        or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this
        element's ancestor 'source') in which the reference group is specified or alluded to. Since
        the annotator's interpretation can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references
        to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. If the
        identification of the reference group is notably uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true".
        Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.<!--add microThemedTextRef, subtract from PROPOSITION version--></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:choice>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:keywordSubRef"/>
        <xs:element name="keywordTagRef" type="thesu:keywordTagRef" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'keywordTagRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:microThemedTextRef"/>
        <xs:element name="microThemedFreeText" type="thesu:microThemedFreeText">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemedFreeText'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:choice>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="keywordRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>The ID of the 'keyword' &#8212;included in the same 'source' as this
        element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'MISC'&#8212; which the annotator wants to qualify as
        particularly relevant in the text of this element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'MISC' should be
        referenced via href in '@ref'. In the case of "implicit" 'keyword' elements or keywords
        contained in 'PROPOSITION' elements, the annotator should indicate to which of the words of
        the 'paraphrasis' of this 'keywordRef''s ancestor 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'PROPOSITION' the
        keywords referenced in each 'keywordRef' correspond. To do so, specify in
        '@wordsInParaphrasis' the numbers of their corresponding words, as delimited by blank space,
        in their order of appearance in 'paraphrasis'. Although in the case of 'THESIS' and 'MISC'
        elements each of their contained keywords will already be provided with a paraphrasing tag
        in the attribute '@namely' of the 'keyword' they refer to, the annotator may always decide
        to also use '@namely' in 'keywordRef' and repeat the paraphrasis, e.g. in order to make the
        isolated 'THESIS' or 'MISC' more easily readable for a human. As to keywords contained in
        'PROPOSITION' elements, the annotator should always tag them directly using '@namely', in a
        form that is compatible with an an authorized spelling in any authority record. In the case
        the annotator has recognized more keywords to be present at the same time with a different
        degree of centrality, or one keyword to be somewhat relevant yet not central to the to
        text's intended meaning, and has decided to include them all, their centrality should be
        ranked in relation to the co-occurring keywords &#8212;whether annotated or merely
        potential&#8212; and specified in '@focus'. In the case the present 'keywordRef' is
        specified for an aggregate-thesis (i.e. a 'THESIS' corresponding to more than one statement
        and in which its '@quantity' has been given a higher value than "1"), but the keyword is not
        relevant to all of the statements in the aggregate, the precise number of its corresponding
        statements should be specified in '@subQuantity'. Minimal syntactic annotation may be added
        for sibling 'keywordRef' elements, in relation to the text of their ancestor 'THESIS',
        'MISC', or 'PROPOSITION', via '@subject' and '@object': '@subject' is to specify which
        co-occurrent keywords are the subjects of the present one (pertinent e.g. to the case of
        adjectives); '@object' to specify which co-occurrent keywords are its objects (pertinent
        e.g. to the case of verbs). It is assumed that the annotated syntactic relationships apply
        to all 'THESIS' and 'MISC' elements sharing the same corresponding keywords, so it is only
        necessary to annotate them once. If, however, the syntactic relationships are different in
        at least two of such 'THESIS' or 'MISC' elements, these will have to be specified for all.
      </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexContent>
      <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:wordsInParaphrasis"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:namely"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:subject"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:object"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:subQuantity"/>
      </xs:restriction>
    </xs:complexContent>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="keywordTagRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via '@ref' in the form of an href, to the authorized
        spelling of a tag contained in the keyword tags authority record associated with the TheSu
        document (i.e. whose URI is referred to in an 'authorityRecord' with '@keywordTags'
        specified as "true"). Just like in 'keyword' elements, the annotator may specify the
        keyword's narrow themes, inasmuch as they are relevant to its present occurrence (since e.g.
        the keyword "body" may in some places be "anatomical-physiological" while in others,
        independently, "chemical-mechanical"), in 'microThemesGroup'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" type="thesu:microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="keywordsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to qualify, via 'keywordRef' elements, one or more terms in the text
        of a 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'PROPOSITION' as particularly relevant keywords: in the case of
        'THESIS' and 'MISC' elements, by pointing each 'keywordRef' to the ID of an
        already-annotated 'keyword'; in the case of 'PROPOSITION' elements, by paraphrasing them
        directly in each 'keywordRef'. More keywords may be present at the same time with a
        different degree of centrality, or one keyword recognized to be somewhat relevant yet not
        central to the to text's intended meaning: the annotator may include all such keywords in
        any order (as long as it is never modified afterwards, which is important since some
        elements may refer to the number of 'keywordRef' elements in their order of appearance), but
        should specify their relative centrality (ranked in relation to that of the co-occurrent
        keywords, whether annotated or not) via the attribute '@focus' of each 'keywordRef'. When
        the 'text' of a 'THESIS' or 'MISC' refers to text segments containing terms that are
        annotated as 'keyword' elements in the same 'source', and these 'keyword' elements are not
        referred to in any of the 'keywordRef' elements of the same 'THESIS' or 'MISC', these are
        assumed to count, for them, as keywords with '@focus' = "5" (least central), and in the case
        of aggregate-theses (i.e. 'THESIS' elements corresponding to more than one statement and in
        which their '@quantity' has been given a higher value than "1") to refer to all of the
        statements in the aggregate; these should therefore be explicited via 'keywordRef' only in
        the case the annotator wanted to indicate their higher centrality, limit their
        '@subQuantity', or specify more details about them.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="keywordRef" type="thesu:keywordRef" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="containsPurpose">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify whether a 'phase' or a range of 'repeatedPhases'
        annotated in a procedural 'sequence' (i.e. in a sequence corresponding to a recipe or set of
        instructions) contains the overall purpose (or one of the purposes) of that same sequence
        (e.g. an expected product, as in "now you have hardened steel", or in an introductory phrase
        "to have hardened steel" opening a recipe, which may be artificially annotated as the final
        phase of a 'sequence' corresponding to that recipe). In such case, specify '@value' as
        "true". As a result, if the parent element of the current 'containsPurpose' is a 'phase',
        that phase will assumed to be the result and purpose (or one of the results and purposes) of
        all the phases that precede it (including the phases contained in other 'phasesGroup'
        elements); if the parent element of the current 'containsPurpose' is instead a
        'repeatedPhases', it will be one of the phases referenced in this to be assumed as the
        result and purpose (or one of the results and purposes) of all the phases that precede it
        (including the phases contained in other 'phasesGroup' elements). In the latter case, the
        relevant phase will be identified in two ways: if the referenced repeated phases of the
        original 'sequence' includes (or references, directly or indirectly) a 'phase' already
        specified as "containing the purpose", that phase will be identified as the purpose in
        'repeatedPhases'; if, instead, the referenced repeated phases of the original 'sequence'
        does not include (or reference, directly or indirectly) a 'phase' already specified as
        "containing the purpose", the final phase referenced in the range of 'repeatedPhases' will
        be identified as the purpose. It is also possible to specify whether the phase thus
        specified as "containing the purpose" is explicitly stated as such for the overall procedure
        in its corresponding text or only inferred by the annotator to be intended as such by the
        sequence's speakers or authors, as conveyed implicitly by their discourse: in the latter
        case, specify '@implicit' as "true". If the identification of the current purpose as such is
        notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". In any case, since the
        identification of the currennt purpose as such presence can be open to debate, references to
        secondary literature may be added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'.
        Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:value"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="definition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify whether the annotated 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' has the
        structure of a definition or not. In the case of 'THESIS' elements, the annotator may prove
        that they are regarded by their speakers to be definitions or not via 'proof', by referring
        to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not
        corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this
        element's ancestor 'source') of the same speakers' presentation of them as definitions or
        denial to them of such status. Since the annotator's choice can be open to debate, it is
        also possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef',
        'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:value"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="elementRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via '@ref' in the form of an href, to an element in a
        TheSu document that is referenced in the parent element. Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:snippet" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="etiologiesGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>If an element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' includes etiologies
        &#8212;i.e. statements on the causes or ends of one or more events&#8212;, the structure of
        each may be annotated here via 'etiology'. One 'etiology' may be added for each distinct
        causal or telic link, as present in the text of the corresponding 'THESIS' or
        'PROPOSITION'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="etiology" type="thesu:etiology" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'etiology' complexType</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="etiology">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate the structure of an etiology &#8212;i.e. a statement on
        the causes or ends of one or more events&#8212;, that is part of the semantic content of a
        'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION'. In the case of 'THESIS' elements, the annotator may prove the
        etiology's presence in their text via 'marker', by referencing text segments interpreted as
        discourse markers signalling the causal or telic relationship between the etiology's members
        (e.g. the words "because" or "for the purpose of"). At least two 'etiologyMember' elements
        must be added, in correspondence with each linked event, cause, and end constituting the
        etiology. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:marker" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:element name="etiologyMember" type="thesu:etiologyMember" minOccurs="2"
        maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'etiologyMember' complexType</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="etiologyMember">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate the details of an event, cause, or end in an etiology
        (i.e. a statement on the causes or ends of one or more events). If this event is one of the
        reported causes in the etiology, specify '@cause' as "true"; if it is one of the reported
        ends, specify '@end' as true; if specified to be neither a cause nor an end, this is assumed
        to be among the events whose sibling (causal or telic) 'etiologyMember' elements are the
        reported causes or ends of. In the case of etiologies contained in 'THESIS' elements, if the
        identification of the current etiology's member as either cause or end is uncertain, specify
        '@uncertain' as "true". The text of the 'etiologyMember' may be specified in different ways.
        In the case of "explicit" 'THESIS' elements, the annotator may: refer to the exact segments
        of text &#8212;in the limits of the 'THESIS''s 'text'&#8212; that report on the present
        event, cause, or end via 'textRef' (note that in this case its corresponding keywords will
        be assumed to be only relevant to this 'etiologyMember', and not to the others which do not
        refer to it); or again refer to the exact segments of text that report on the present event,
        cause, or end, but also provide them with their own macro- and micro-thematic annotation,
        via 'fullyThemedTextRef' (which is useful when the annotator wants to specify the most
        relevant narrow themes of an event, cause, or end without presenting them as central to the
        whole etiology, i.e. without specifying them in the 'thesisType''s child ''macroThemesGroup'
        or 'microThemesGroup'); or refer to another annotated 'THESIS' or 'MISC' &#8212;figuring in
        its whole in this etiology as either event, cause, or end&#8212; via 'elementRef'; or freely
        type in the span of text reporting on the present event, cause, or end, as it is specified
        in the 'paraphrasis' of the 'THESIS' (which is especially useful when the reported event,
        cause, or end includes implicit keywords, not corresponding to any segment of text), and
        again, possibly, provide it with its own macro- and micro-thematic annotation, via
        'fullyThemedFreeText' (note that in this case the keywords corresponding to the text span of
        the 'paraphrasis' will be assumed to be relevant to this 'etiologyMember', and not to the
        others which do not refer to it). In the case of "implicit" 'THESIS' elements, the annotator
        may: refer to another annotated 'THESIS' or 'MISC' &#8212;figuring in its whole in this
        etiology as either event, cause, or end&#8212; via 'elementRef'; or freely type in the span
        of text reporting on the present event, cause, or end, as it is specified in the
        'paraphrasis' of the "implicit" 'THESIS', and possibly provide it with its own macro- and
        micro-thematic annotation, via 'fullyThemedFreeText' (in this case, the annotator will be
        able to specify the most relevant broad or narrow themes of this member without presenting
        them as central to the whole etiology, i.e. without having to specify them in the
        'thesisType''s child 'macroThemesGroup' or 'microThemesGroup' &#8212; also note that in this
        case the keywords corresponding to the text span of the 'paraphrasis' will be assumed to be
        relevant to this 'etiologyMember', and not to the others which do not refer to it). In the
        case of 'PROPOSITION' elements, the annotator may: refer to another annotated 'PROPOSITION'
        &#8212;figuring in its whole in this etiology as either event, cause, or end&#8212; via
        'elementRef'; or freely type in the span of text reporting on the present event, cause, or
        end, as it is specified in the 'paraphrasis' of the 'PROPOSITION', and possibly provide it
        with its own macro- and micro-thematic annotation, via 'fullyThemedFreeText' (in this case,
        the annotator will be able to specify the most relevant narrow themes of this event, cause,
        or end without presenting them as central to the whole etiology, i.e. without having to
        specify them in the 'propositionType''s or 'thesisType''s child 'macroThemesGroup' or
        'microThemesGroup' &#8212; also note that in this case the keywords corresponding to the
        text span of the 'paraphrasis' will be assumed to be relevant to this 'etiologyMember', and
        not to the others which do not refer to it). Finally, the annotator may provide a clear and
        concise presentation, in the language that has been chosen for the TheSu corpus, of the
        current 'etiologyMember' in 'paraphrasis', as long as this is faithful to the
        'etiologyMember''s associated text or element. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:choice>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:textRef"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:fullyThemedTextRef"/>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="fullyThemedFreeText" type="thesu:fullyThemedFreeText">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'fullyThemedFreeText'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:choice>
      <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:cause" default="false"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:end" default="false"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="externalRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to cite a passage in the secondary literature that is relevant to
        the annotation of the parent element and useful to compare. The bibliographical reference
        must be inserted in '@bibliographyRef', in the form of an href to either the URI of a
        bibliographic record in the bibliography associated with the TheSu document (i.e. whose URI
        is referred to in an 'authorityRecord' with '@bibliographicRecords' specified as "true") or
        to the ID of one of the 'bibliographyRef' elements annotated in the 'bibliography' of the
        'source'. The beginning and ending of the passage in the text (e.g. page, note, ...) can be
        specified either in '@biblLocusRefFrom' and '@biblLocusRefTo', in the form of the URI of a
        locus indicator in a digital source, or freely in '@biblLocusFree', in the form of a string.
        The passage can also be quoted in 'biblQuote'. The annotator can also use 'paraphrasis' to
        provide a clear and concise paraphrasis of this passage, in the language that has been
        chosen for the TheSu corpus. If the referenced passage cites or quotes a specific text
        segment corresponding to the current element (note that this does not apply to 'PROPOSITION'
        elements), its beginning can be specified in '@locusRefFrom', and its ending in
        '@locusRefTo', in the form of the URI of a locus indicator contained in the current digital
        source (i.e. contained in the digital source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'), e.g. of a 'tei:milestone' or an HTML 'p'. If
        the text is also quoted verbatim in the referenced work, in the context that is relevant to
        this 'externalRef', the quote can be specified in 'text'. In contrast, if the reference to
        the content of the current element is not explicit in the passage of the external source,
        but is only inferred by the annotator to be intended in the context of its discourse or
        macrotext, specify '@implicit' as "true". If it is recognized to be actually extraneous to
        the author's intent (yet relevant to the annotation for any reason), specify '@extrinsic' as
        "true". If the presence or intepretation of the reference is notably uncertain, e.g. due to
        an ambiguity in the text, specify '@uncertain' as "true". Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:biblQuote" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:text" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:locusRefFrom"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:locusRefTo"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:bibliographyRef"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:biblLocusRefFrom"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:biblLocusRefTo"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:biblLocusFree"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit" default="false"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:extrinsic" default="false"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:uncertain" default="false"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="follows">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which a 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' does
        not follow chronologically on the 'phase' or 'phasesGroup' that precedes it within the same
        'sequence' element, because of a jump or return at the corresponding point of the
        succession. To reference the 'phasesGroup' or 'phase' chronologically followed by the
        current 'phase' or 'repeatedPhases', the annotator may use '@phasesRef'. If the referenced
        'phasesGroup' or 'phase' elements make up a range of more than one phase, it is assumed that
        the current 'phase' or 'repeatedPhases' chronologically follows the last phase of such
        range. It the current 'phase' or 'repeatedPhases' is contained in a 'THESIS', the annotator
        may prove that the sequence's speakers or authors intend the phase or range of repeated
        phases to follow precisely on the phase referenced in '@phasesRef' by using 'proof' and
        pointing to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the annotator's identification of the
        phase chronologically preceding the current 'phase' or 'repeatedPhases' in the succession
        can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature,
        through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'; the neutral 'externalRef' can be
        also added to 'follows' elements within 'sequence' elements contained in 'PROPOSITION'
        elements. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="fullyThemedFreeText">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to select a portion of the text corresponding to a descendant
        element of a 'PROPOSITION' or "implicit" 'THESIS', as annotated in these latter's
        'paraphrasis', by typing it in 'freeText' in the free form of a string, while possibly also
        specifying its broad or narrow themes in 'macroThemesGroup' or 'microThemesGroup'. A
        'macroThemesGroup' should be used when the annotator recognizes that the text portion should
        be annotated with a different 'macroTheme' or hierarchy of 'macroTheme' elements than the
        one specified for this element's ancestor 'PROPOSITION' or 'THESIS' in the
        'propositionType''s or 'thesisType''s child 'macroThemesGroup'. A 'microThemesGroup' should
        be used when the annotator recognizes that the text portion should be annotated with a
        different set or focal arrangement of 'microTheme' elements than the one specified in the
        'propositionType''s or 'thesisType''s child 'microThemesGroup'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="freeText" type="thesu:freeText">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>This is to select a portion of the text corresponding to a descendant
            element of a 'PROPOSITION' or "implicit" 'THESIS', as annotated in its 'paraphrasis', by
            typing it in the free form of a string. The annotator should ensure that the wording
            corresponds exactly to a text span in the pertinent 'paraphrasis'. To signal points of
            discontinuity in the quotation use '...'.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="macroThemesGroup" type="thesu:macroThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'macroThemesGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" type="thesu:microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="locus">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide the coordinates of one or more relevant segments of the
        text from a single source. The source's title must be specified in '@title'. To refer to the
        specific passages, whether in the free form of a written reference or by linking to text
        segments in a digital source, the annotator may use one or more 'locusRef'. To prove the
        relevance of the referenced passages, the annotator may use 'proof' and point to textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source')
        of the indicated reference. Since the identification of the relevant segments of text can be
        open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature, through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. The identification of the relevant
        passages may sometimes be uncertain due to an ambiguity in the text: in such cases, the
        annotator may use '@rank' to specify how likely is each annotated 'locus' to be the truly
        relevant one with respect to its siblings, by giving it a value between "1" (most likely)
        and "4" (least likely). </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:locusRef" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:title"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="historyDetails">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to add further details in the case a 'macroTheme' has been annotated
        as "historical", i.e. narrative. The kind of historical information (e.g. concerning
        "actions", "ideas", etc.) may be specified via a tag in 'historyType'. The time in which the
        reported events take place (e.g. "past", "present", etc., with respects to the time of the
        narrative statements) may be specified via a tag in 'historyTime'. If the narration concerns
        one or more specific individuals, their names or group designators may be specified in
        'historyOnPersons'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="historyType" type="thesu:historyType">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'historyType' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="historyTime" type="thesu:historyTime">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'historyTime' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="historyOnPersons" type="thesu:historyOnPersons" minOccurs="0"
        maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'historyOnPersons' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="historyOnPersons">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via one or more 'name' elements, which individuals an
        element that has been annotated as "historical" (i.e. narrative) in theme reports on. If
        this is uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". In the case the statements are ambiguous
        enough to support an identification with more than one individuals, the annotator can decide
        to specify the names of all, but must choose one or more as the most likely to be referred
        to in the historical statements by attributing to them a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as
        e.g. "1" the '@rank' in their corresponding 'name' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that
        of the others. When multiple 'name' elements are provided with the same rank, it is assumed
        that the annotator understands the historical statements to report on all of their
        corresponding individuals at the same time. In the case no 'name' element is provided with
        rank "1", it is assumed that the ambiguity is too high to propose a reasonable
        identification (but note that at least one individual, provided with rank "2", will still
        have to be favoured by the annotator). The annotator may prove the presence of such
        uncertainties via 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital
        source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the
        attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the ambiguity (note that this is
        not used as evidence for the ranking of the individuals' names; this can be proven via the
        child element 'proof' of each 'name'). Since the recognition of the ambiguity can be open to
        debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature, through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro' and 'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="name" type="thesu:name" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'name' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="historyTime">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via '@historyTimeTag', the time in which the events
        reported by an element that has been annotated as "historical", i.e. narrative, in theme
        take place (e.g. "past", "present", etc., with respects to the time of the narrative
        statements). If this is uncertain (e.g. a report in present tense may sometimes ambiguously
        refer to the past), specify '@uncertain' as "true". In the case of such ambiguity, the
        annotator's choice may be supported, through 'proof', by referring to relevant textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source'). Since the recognized time of the events can be open to debate, it is also
        possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:historyTimeTag"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="historyType">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via '@historyTypeTag', what kind of historical
        information (e.g. concerning "actions", "ideas", etc.) is conveyed by an element that has
        been annotated as "historical", i.e. narrative, in theme. If this is uncertain (e.g. an
        ambiguous reference to what a philosopher &#171;said&#187; may be sometimes interpreted as
        either a report on "sayings" or on "writings", depending on the availability of other
        information), specify '@uncertain' as "true". In the case of such ambiguity, the annotator's
        choice may be supported, through 'proof', by referring to relevant textual evidence (i.e.
        text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose
        URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the
        recognized kind of history can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to
        secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:historyTypeTag"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="macroTheme">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>Use '@macroThemeTag' to specify the broad theme (e.g. "historical",
        "axiological", etc.) of this element's ancestor 'THESIS', 'MISC', 'PROPOSITION', or
        'phasesGroup'. If the annotated broad theme for a 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'phasesGroup' is
        recognized to be either representative or unrepresentative of the thematic
        (macro-)distinctions that are held or perceived by its speakers (inasmuch as can be inferred
        from the discourse or macrotext in which the same 'THESIS' or 'MISC' is included), the
        annotator may specify this awareness or unawareness on the speakers' part via 'conscious'.
        If the broad theme of a 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'phasesGroup' is unclear (e.g. a statement
        concerning a procedure to prepare a medication may be ambiguous in its speakers' intention
        to present it as "methodological", i.e. directly instructive, or "historical", i.e.
        descriptive of an existing procedure, not in itself recommending to follow it), this may be
        specified in '@uncertain'. In the case of such ambiguity, the annotator's choice may be
        supported, through 'proof', by referring to relevant textual evidence (i.e. text segments in
        a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to
        in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the recognition of a
        broad theme can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. If the annotated theme
        is "historical", i.e. narrative, details on the historical report may be specified in
        'historyDetails'; if the annotated theme is "metatextual", i.e. commenting on one or more
        statements or segments of text, details on the commented texts may be specified in
        'metatextDetails'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element name="historyDetails" type="thesu:historyDetails" minOccurs="0"
        maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'historyDetails' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="metatextDetails" type="thesu:metatextDetails" minOccurs="0"
        maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'metatextDetails' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:macroThemeTag"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="macroThemesGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the broad theme (e.g. "historical", "axiological", etc.)
        of a 'THESIS', 'MISC', 'PROPOSITION', or 'phasesGroup', via 'macroTheme'. More 'macroTheme'
        elements may be included in hierarchical succession, since some broad themes may specify
        some others, e.g.: a general indication on how to prepare a medication may be tagged as
        "methodological", but a proposition describing how an ancient population prepared a
        medication may be rather tagged as "historical" &#8212; in the latter case, the annotator
        may decide to add a second 'macroTheme' to tag the proposition also, and subordinately, as
        "methodological". The meaningful successions of 'macroTheme' elements are established by the
        inventory of tags that has been chosen by the annotator, as defined in the macro-themes'
        authority record associated with the TheSu corpus (i.e. whose URI is referred to in an
        'authorityRecord' with '@macroThemeTags' specified as "true").</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="macroTheme" type="thesu:macroTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'macroTheme' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="matchingPhases">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>Generic complexType used by the elements 'matchingPropositionPhases' and
        'correspondingPhases'. It allows to reference a range of 'phasesGroup' or 'phase' elements
        within a 'sequence' contained in either a 'THESIS' or a 'PROPOSITION', in the form of a
        coded string. It also allows to provide textual evidence for the reference through 'proof',
        and to cite secondary sources thorugh 'scholarPro', 'scholarContra', and 'externalRef'.
        Finally, it allows to add custom elements through 'customElement'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:differencesInCorrespondence"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="matchingSequence">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is a generic complexType used by the elements
        'correspondingPropositionSequence', 'matchingPropositionSequence' and
        'correspondingThesisSequence'. It allows to reference via '@sequenceRef' a 'sequence'
        contained in a 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION', in the form of an href to its ID. It also allows
        to add custom elements through 'customElement'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:sequenceRef" use="required"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="metatext">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide the details of a statement or segment of text (whether
        continuous or discontinuous) that is commented on by a metatextual statement. In the case
        the metatext concerns a 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' in a TheSu document, the annotator
        may simply use 'elementRef' to link to it. In the case the metatext concerns a segment of
        text which is not annotated in this way, the annotator may first specify, if this is a
        quotation, the quoted individuals or groups in 'quotedSpeaker', and then provide its
        coordinates (whether in the free form of a written reference or by linking to a text segment
        in a digital source) in 'quotedLocus'. To prove the relevance of the referenced statement or
        segment of text, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the indicated
        reference. Since the identification of the relevant statement or segment of text can be open
        to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature, through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. The identification of the statement or
        segment of text that is commented on by the metatext may sometimes be uncertain due to an
        ambiguity in its phrasing: in such cases, the annotator may use '@rank' to specify how
        likely is each annotated 'metatext' to be the truly relevant one with respect to its
        siblings, by giving it a value between "1" (most likely) and "4" (least likely). Custom
        elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="quotedSpeaker" type="thesu:speakersGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'speakersGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="quotedLocus" type="thesu:textLocus" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'textLocus' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="metatextDetails">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to add further details in the case a 'macroTheme' has been annotated
        as "metatextual", i.e. commenting on one or more statements or segments of text. To provide
        the details of each distinct statement or segment of text that is commented on, the
        annotator may use a 'metatext' . If their identification is uncertain, specify '@uncertain'
        as "true". In the case the metatext is ambiguous enough to support an identification, for
        its reference, with more than one statement or segment of text (or more than one group of
        statements or segments of text), the annotator can decide to provide the details of all, but
        must choose one or more as the most likely to be commented on by the metatext by attributing
        to them a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the '@rank' in their corresponding
        'metatext' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the others. When multiple 'metatext'
        elements are provided with the same rank, it is assumed that the annotator understands the
        metatext to comment on all of their corresponding statements or segments of text at the same
        time. In the case no 'metatext' element is provided with rank "1", this means that the
        ambiguity is too high to propose a reasonable identification (but note that at least one
        referenced statement or segment of text, provided with rank "2", will still have to be
        favoured by the annotator). The annotator may prove the presence of such uncertainties via
        'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the ambiguity (note that this is not used as
        evidence for the ranking of the referenced statements or segments of text; this can be
        proven via the child element 'proof' of each 'metatext'). Since the recognition of the
        ambiguity can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be
        added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="metatext" type="thesu:metatext" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'metatext' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="microTheme">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via '@microThemeTag', the narrow theme (e.g. "military",
        "psychological", etc.) of an element's ancestor 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'PROPOSITION'. If the
        annotated broad theme for a 'THESIS' or 'MISC' is recognized to be either representative or
        unrepresentative of the thematic (micro-)distinctions that are held or perceived by its
        speakers (inasmuch as can be inferred from the discourse or macrotext in which the same
        'THESIS' or 'MISC' is included), the annotator may specify this awareness or unawareness on
        the speakers' part via 'conscious'. In the case the annotator has recognized more narrow
        themes to be present at the same time with a different degree of centrality, or one narrow
        theme to be somewhat relevant yet not central to the to text's intended meaning, and has
        decided to include them, their centrality should be ranked in relation to the co-existent
        micro-themes &#8212;whether annotated or merely potential&#8212; and specified in '@focus'.
        To prove the relevance of the present micro-theme to the text of its corresponding 'THESIS'
        or 'MISC', the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to relevant textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the
        recognition of a narrow theme can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references
        to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. The
        thematic attribution to a 'THESIS' or 'MISC' may sometimes be uncertain due to an ambiguity
        in their text: in such cases, the annotator may use '@rank' to specify how likely is each
        annotated 'microTheme' to be the truly relevant one with respect to its siblings sharing its
        '@focus', by giving it a value between "1" (most likely) and "4" (least likely). In the case
        the present 'microTheme' is specified for an aggregate-thesis (i.e. a 'THESIS' corresponding
        to more than one statement and in which its '@quantity' has been given a higher value than
        "1"), but the narrow-theme is not relevant to all of the statements in the aggregate, the
        precise number of its corresponding statements should be specified in '@subQuantity'. Custom
        elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:subQuantity"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
  </xs:complexType>


  <xs:complexType name="microThemedFreeText">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation> This is to annotate in 'freeText' a freely typed text in the form of a
        string, either selected from a portion of the text corresponding to a descendant element of
        a 'PROPOSITION' or "implicit" 'THESIS', as annotated in these latter's 'paraphrasis', or
        unrelated to it, while possibly also specifying its narrow themes in 'microThemesGroup', in
        the same way as would be done for a 'keyword'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="freeText" type="thesu:freeText">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a freely typed text in the form of a string, either
            selected from a portion of the text corresponding to a descendant element of a
            'PROPOSITION' or "implicit" 'THESIS', as annotated in these latter's 'paraphrasis', or
            unrelated to it. In the former case, the annotator should ensure that the wording
            corresponds exactly to a text span in the pertinent 'paraphrasis', and signal any points
            of discontinuity in the quotation using '...'.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" type="thesu:microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="microThemesGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via 'microTheme' elements, one or more of the narrow
        themes (e.g. "military", "psychological", etc.) of a 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'PROPOSITION'.
        More narrow themes may be present at the same time with a different degree of centrality, or
        one narrow theme recognized to be somewhat relevant yet not central to the to text's
        intended meaning: the annotator may include all such themes in any order, but should specify
        their relative centrality (ranked in relation to the co-existent micro-themes, whether
        annotated or not) via the attribute '@focus' of each 'microTheme'. If the recognition of the
        narrow themes or of their relative centrality is uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true".
        In the case the text is ambiguous enough to support the recognition of more than one
        micro-theme or group of micro-themes for the same degree of centrality (e.g. an ambiguous
        statement about water's behaviour with respect to nutrition may either be "botanical" or
        "zoophysiological", if not both), the annotator can decide to include them all, but must
        choose one or more as the most likely to be the truly relevant narrow themes by attributing
        to them a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the '@rank' in their corresponding
        'microTheme' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the others. When multiple
        'microTheme' elements are provided with the same rank and with the same '@focus', it is
        assumed that the annotator understands all of their corresponding narrow themes to be most
        likely to be the truly relevant ones for their degree of centrality. In the case no
        'microTheme' is provided with rank "1", among those which share the same '@focus', it is
        assumed that the text's ambiguity is too high to propose a reasonable choice for the
        corresponding degree of centrality (but note that at least one alleged narrow theme,
        provided with rank "2", will still have to be favoured by the annotator). The annotator may
        prove the presence of such uncertainties via 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e.
        text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose
        URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the
        ambiguity (note that this is not used as evidence for the ranking of the alleged
        micro-themes; this can be proven via the child element 'proof' of each 'micro-Theme'). Since
        the recognition of the ambiguity can be open to debate, it is also possible to add
        references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="microTheme" type="thesu:microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="name">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via '@name' in the form of an href, to the name or group
        designator of an individual or group that is relevant to the parent element. To prove the
        relevance of such an individual or group, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source')
        in which the individual or group is mentioned or alluded to. Since the identification of the
        relevant individual or group can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to
        secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. The
        identification may sometimes be uncertain due to an ambiguity in the text: in such cases,
        the annotator may use '@rank' to specify how likely is each annotated 'name' to be the truly
        relevant one with respect to its siblings, by giving it a value between "1" (most likely)
        and "4" (least likely). Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:name" use="required"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank" default="1"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="newPhases">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a new succession of one or more phases of the same
        sequence, along with details on each phase (involved objects or ingredients, duration,
        etc.). When descendants of a 'THESIS', these phases are new &#8212; in the context of the
        'phasesGroup' they are part of &#8212; in the sense that they have not been already
        annotated in the same or in another 'sequence' (contained either in the current 'sequence''s
        own ancestor 'THESIS' or in another of the same discourse or macrotext), neither being a
        range of already annotated phases of the same sequence meant to be repeated at the current
        point of the sequence, nor being part of a different sequence intended by their speakers or
        authors to be possibly substituted by the current sequence, presented as a variant procedure
        or diverging account of the former. Note that in the case of procedural sequences (i.e.
        recipes or sets of instructions), any number of new 'phase' elements can be specified to
        contain the purpose (or one of the purposes) of the procedure as a whole (e.g. an expected
        product, as in "now you have hardened steel", or in an introductory phrase "to have hardened
        steel" opening a recipe, which may be artificially annotated as the final phase of a
        'sequence' corresponding to that recipe), using their child element 'containsPurpose': each
        'phase' which is specified as "containing the purpose" will be in this way specified to be
        the result and purpose (or one of the results and purposes) of all the phases that precede
        it (including the phases contained in other 'phasesGroup' elements); if the current
        'newPhases' is contained in a 'sequence' intended by its speakers or authors as a variant of
        another annotated procedural 'sequence', and the purpose (or one of the purposes) of the
        current sequence matches the purpose of the original sequence (e.g. the purpose of both
        procedures is to make hardened steel), the annotator should not specify a new 'phase' of the
        current sequence as containing that purpose, but a 'repeatedPhases' element instead,
        referencing the range of phases of the original 'sequence' which includes (or references,
        directly or indirectly) that 'phase' already specified as "containing the purpose" whose
        contained purpose matches the said purpose of the current sequence. For 'phasesGroup'
        elements descendants of a 'PROPOSITION', only 'newPhases' elements are allowed. If the
        'phasesGroup' is a descendant of a 'THESIS', and does contain a succession of phases which
        have already been annotated in the same or in another 'sequence' and which are re-employed
        &#8212; possibly diverging on specific details &#8212; at the current point of the sequence
        (e.g. because a range of steps in the same procedure are meant to be repeated at the current
        point of the sequence, or the current sequence is presented in a procedural text as a
        variant recipe of another, already annotated, recipe in the same text for the same product,
        or as a modification of another, already annotated, recipe in the same text resulting in a
        different product) the annotator should use 'repeatedPhases' instead. Add a 'phase' for each
        phase of the current portion of the sequence. The phases must follow each other in the
        correct chronological succession, regardless of their original order of presentation.
        Specified jumps and returns in the succession are allowed: the annotator may use for any
        phase its child element 'follows' and specify to which 'phase' of the overall 'sequence' it
        chronologically comes next.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="phase" type="thesu:phase" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phase' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="object">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify an object or ingredient involved in a 'phase' annotated
        within a 'sequence', while possibly also providing details on its functions, quantites,
        measures, and relation with preceding phases of the same sequence. Depending on the text of,
        and keywords referenced in, the 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' containing this sequence, and on
        the already annotated 'object' elements, the object may be identified in four different
        ways: in the case the object has been already annotated in another 'phase' within a
        'sequence' (contained either in the same 'PROPOSITION' or in the same or in another
        'THESIS'), and shares the same corresponding text, keywords, or part of the representation
        of the semantic content of a 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' as the current object (e.g. in the
        sequence "one must take the steel", "and bring it to red-yellow incandescence" the second
        phase still involves the object "steel" as mentioned in the first phase), by referencing
        such already annotated 'object' in 'objectRef'; in the case the object has not already been
        annotated, and corresponds to one or more of the keywords annotated for the 'THESIS' or
        'PROPOSITION', by referring to these keywords via 'keywordSubRef'; otherwise, in the case
        the object is hardly associated with any specific keyword, is included in a 'THESIS', and is
        mentioned explicitly in its text, by directly referencing the text segments that correspond
        to it via 'microThemedTextRef', possibly associating the resulting text span with its proper
        narrow themes; or, if the object is hardly associated with keywords, is involved either
        implicitly in a 'THESIS' or in a 'PROPOSITION', and is mentioned in the 'THESIS''s or
        'PROPOSITION''s child 'paraphrasis', by freely typing as a string in 'microThemedFreeText'
        the text span corresponding to the object as specified in that 'paraphrasis', while also
        providing it, if possible, with its own micro-thematic annotation. It is possible to combine
        the first two ways of identifying the object with the latter two. This is necessary when the
        object does correspond to an already annotated object or a keyword, but is characterized in
        the text or semantic content of a 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' expressing the current 'phase'
        in ways that are new or can hardly be represented as keywords (e.g. when the object involved
        in a phase is not simply "steel", but "high-quality steel with optimized toughness, soft
        core, and hard surface", which includes the keyword "steel" while also characterizing it
        extensively, or when a first phase reads "heat the steel in a furnace" and a following
        phase, still involving the "steel" of the first, is "hammer it while it is still
        incandescent", expressing "while it is still incandescent" as a new characterization of the
        same object). In such cases, the annotator may use either 'microThemedTextRef', to textually
        reference explicit characterizations of the object in 'THESIS' elements, or
        'microThemedFreeText', to report semantic characterizations annotated in the 'paraphrasis'
        of 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' elements (while possibly also specifying their narrow themes).
        In order to make the isolated TheSu document more easily readable for a human, it is
        possible to provide in 'object''s own child element 'paraphrasis' a clear and concise
        presentation of the object and its characterizations, in the language that has been chosen
        for the TheSu corpus and consistently with all its other annotated details. When the
        'object', in the context of a 'sequence' contained in a 'THESIS', is not explicitly
        mentioned in the text corresponding to the 'phase' which involves it, but its involvement in
        the phase is only inferred by the annotator to be intended by the 'THESIS''s speakers or
        authors, and communicated implicitly by the discourse or macrotext this is included in,
        '@implcit' should be specified as "true". If the implicit involvement of the object in the
        current phase is notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". To prove the
        implicit involvement of the object in the current phase, the annotator may use 'proof' and
        refer to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding
        or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this
        element's ancestor 'source'). Since the annotator's recognition of the object's implicit
        involvement can be open to debate, references to secondary literature may be added through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'; the neutral 'externalRef', adaptable to
        other ends, can be also added to 'object' elements involved in 'sequence' elements within
        'PROPOSITION' elements. The object's reported or intended quantity in the current phase
        involving it may be specified in 'objectQuantity'. The object's reported or intended
        measures and quantitative features beyond its amount (such as size, temperature, hardness,
        etc.) in the same phase may be specified in 'objectMeasuresGroup'. If the full
        characterization of the object includes comparisons with other objects not specifiable under
        'objectQuantity' or 'objectMeasuresGroup', each of these compared objects may be referenced
        in 'relativeTo' (e.g. "a paste similar in nature to the mixture prepared previously", or
        even with objects otherwise unrelated to the described process, as in "a product with
        properties similar to those of wet clay", or "a residue resembling tree sap"). Any 'object',
        in fact, can be provided with an ID in '@xml:id', enabling such references. If the object
        involved in the current phase is the product of events or actions annotated in preceding
        phases of the same 'sequence' &#8211;having the object been altered in those phases in any
        way including transformations, combinations with other ingredients, and removals of
        portions&#8211; this should be specified in 'productOf'. Note that every time the same
        object is involved in subsequent phases, but endures any alteration in the earlier phase
        (e.g. in the sequence "heat the steel in a furnace", "and then hammer it while it is still
        incandescent"), in the later phase it should be annotated as a 'productOf' that earlier
        phase. Finally, if the object is involved in a procedural 'phase' (i.e. a step within a
        recipe or set of instructions), its function as an instrument, ingredient, or both can be
        specified in 'objectFunction'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.
        Definition to be slightly revise to account for use within 'relativeTo' elements.
        <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexContent>
      <xs:restriction base="thesu:objectModel">
        <xs:sequence>
          <xs:choice minOccurs="0">
            <xs:element name="objectRef" type="thesu:objectRef">
              <xs:annotation>
                <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
              </xs:annotation>
            </xs:element>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:keywordSubRef"/>
          </xs:choice>
          <xs:choice minOccurs="0">
            <xs:element ref="thesu:microThemedTextRef"/>
            <xs:element name="microThemedFreeText" type="thesu:microThemedFreeText">
              <xs:annotation>
                <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemedFreeText'
                  complexType.</xs:documentation>
              </xs:annotation>
            </xs:element>
          </xs:choice>
          <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasisSimple" minOccurs="0">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasisSimple'
                complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:element name="relativeTo" type="thesu:object" minOccurs="0">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>This is for cases in which the full characterization of an 'object'
                involves comparisons with any number of other objects, provided such comparisons are
                not specifiable under 'objectQuantity' or 'objectMeasuresGroup' (e.g. "a paste
                similar in nature to the mixture prepared previously", or even with objects
                otherwise unrelated to the described process, such as "a product with properties
                similar to those of wet clay", or "a residue resembling tree sap"). Since
                'relativeTo' elements are annotated exactly like 'object' elements, refer to the
                'object' complexType for instructions. Definition to be extended and improved.
                <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:element name="objectQuantity" type="thesu:objectQuantity" minOccurs="0">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectQuantity'
                complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:element name="objectMeasuresGroup" type="thesu:objectMeasuresGroup" minOccurs="0">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectMeasuresGroup'
                complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:element name="productOf" type="thesu:productOf" minOccurs="0">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'productOf' complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:element name="objectFunction" type="thesu:objectFunction" minOccurs="0">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectFunction'
                complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
          <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"/>
        </xs:sequence>
        <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
        <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
      </xs:restriction>
    </xs:complexContent>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectFunction">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify whether an object involved in a procedural phase within a
        sequence (i.e. in a step within a recipe or set of instructions) has the function of an
        instrument, ingredient, or both. If the object is involved in the phase as an instrument,
        specify '@instrument' as "true"; if as an ingredient, specify '@ingredient' as "true". If
        the object is involved in a phase within a 'sequence' contained in a 'THESIS', and the
        object's function in that phase reported or intended by the 'THESIS''s speakers or authors,
        as conveyed by the full discourse or macrotext this is included in, is notably uncertain,
        '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". The annotator may prove that the object's function
        corresponds to the one specified via 'proof', by referring to pertinent textual evidence
        (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source
        whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since
        the annotator's interpretation of the object's function can be open to debate, it is also
        possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:instrument"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ingredient"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectMeasure">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify an object's reported or intended single measure or
        quantitative feature other than its amount (such as size, temperature, hardness, etc.) in
        the context of a 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' (e.g. "20 centimeters" for the object
        "iron bar" in the phase "heat a 20 cm long iron bar over the hearth"; "760 Celsius degrees"
        for the object "steel blade" in the phase "when the steel blade reaches roughly 760&#176; C,
        they quickly immerse it in water"; "700 grams" for the object "hammer" in the phase "a
        heavy-duty hammer with a 700-gram head was used to harden the copper bar"). The base measure
        can be specified as a number in '@number'. If a measurement unit is present (e.g.
        "centimeter", "Celsius degree", etc.), this can be specied in '@measurementUnit' via one or
        more tags, each expressed as an href to the URI of an authorized spelling in an authority
        record associated with the TheSu corpus (i.e. an authority record whose URI is referred to
        in an 'authorityRecord' with '@objectDetailsTags' specified as "true"). In
        '@measurementType', it is possible to specify the kind of the present measure or
        quantitative feature (e.g. "size", "temperature", "hardness", etc.) via one or more tags,
        each expressed as an href to the URI of an authorized spelling in an authority record
        associated with the TheSu corpus. If the measure is approximative (e.g. "roughly 760&#176;
        C" or "just enough"), '@approximative' may be specified as "true". If the measure is not
        numerical (e.g. "red-hot", or "as hard as possible"), '@number' should not be provided with
        a value, and the non-numerical measure should be reported as a string in '@nonNumerical'. If
        the measure is relative to any attribute of other objects (e.g. the object "copper bar" for
        the measure "500 grams" in the phase "hammer the bar using a hammer with a head weighing 500
        grams for each centimeter of the bar's thickness", or even objects otherwise unrelated to
        the described process, as in "cool the metal until its temperature is lower than body
        temperature", or "shape the lump until its diameter matches that of a hen's egg"), any
        number of such objects may be referenced in 'relativeTo'. If the full measure combines a
        base quantitative value with any number of additional quantities (e.g. in the phase "anneal
        the heated bar into a 40 cm long, 20 cm wide, 10 cm deep container filled with sand, plus 10
        cm in length for each additional 5 cm of the metal bar", or in the succession "they
        traditionally boil the fabric in a 50&#176;C dye solution, but after one hour of soaking,
        they increase the latter's temperature by 10&#176;C to enhance color absorption"), each of
        such additions to the initial measure may be added in 'measureAddition' (note that for
        repeated objects it is also possible to not specify any base measure in the phase where they
        are repeated, and only annotate the additions, as would be required in the succession "they
        traditionally boil the fabric in a 50&#176;C dye solution, but after one hour of soaking,
        they increase the latter's temperature by 10&#176;C", where the second phase re-employs the
        "dye solution" of the first while increasing the measure of its temperature). If the
        specified measure or quantitative feature concerns only a specific portion of the object
        (e.g. the portion "head" of the object "hammer" for the measure "700-gram" in the phase "a
        heavy-duty hammer with a 700-gram head was used to harden the copper bar"), such portion can
        be specified in '@where' in the free form of a string; if this attribute is not assigned
        with a value, it is assumed that the specified measure or quantitative feature concerns the
        object as a whole. If the object is involved in a phase within a 'sequence' contained in a
        'THESIS', and the measure or quantitative feature reported or intended by the 'THESIS''s
        speakers or authors, as conveyed by the full discourse or macrotext this is included in, is
        notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". The annotator may prove that the
        measure corresponds to the one specified via 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e.
        text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose
        URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the
        measure's overall quantification. Since the annotator's interpretation of the object's
        measure can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be
        added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="relativeTo" type="thesu:object" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which an object's reported or intended base
            measure or quantitative feature other than its amount is relative to any number of other
            objects (e.g. the measure "500 grams" as related to the object "copper bar" in the phase
            "hammer the bar using a hammer with a head weighing 500 grams for each centimeter of the
            bar's thickness", or even with objects otherwise unrelated to the described process, as
            in "cool the metal until its temperature is lower than body temperature", or "shape the
            lump until its diameter matches that of a hen's egg"). Since 'relativeTo' elements are
            annotated exactly like 'object' elements, refer to the 'object' complexType for
            instructions. Definition to be extended and improved.
            <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:measureAddition" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:measurementUnit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:measurementType"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:where"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectMeasuresGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify any number of an object's reported or intended measures
        or quantitative features other than its amount (such as size, temperature, hardness, etc.).
        Add an 'objectMeasure' for each of such distinct measures.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="objectMeasure" type="thesu:objectMeasure" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectMeasure' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectModel">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>Generic complexType used by the complexTypes 'object', 'addedObject', and
        'alteredObject'. It allows to identify an object involved or mentioned in a phase or range
        of phases within a 'sequence' and specify its details. In order to make the isolated TheSu
        document more easily readable for a human, it is possible to provide in 'paraphrasis' a
        clear and concise presentation of the object and its characterizations, in the language that
        has been chosen for the TheSu corpus and consistently with all its other annotated details.
        It also allows to provide textual evidence of the object's involvement in that phase or
        range of phases via 'proof', and to cite secondary sources thorugh 'scholarPro',
        'scholarContra', and 'externalRef'. Finally, it allows to add custom elements through
        'customElement'. Please, refer to the 'object', 'addedObject', 'alteredObject', and
        'relativeTo' complexTypes for further information.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:choice minOccurs="0">
        <xs:element name="objectRef" type="thesu:objectRef">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:keywordSubRef"/>
      </xs:choice>
      <xs:choice minOccurs="0">
        <xs:element ref="thesu:microThemedTextRef"/>
        <xs:element name="microThemedFreeText" type="thesu:microThemedFreeText">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemedFreeText'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:choice>
      <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasisSimple" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasisSimple' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="relativeTo" type="thesu:object" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --> Please, refer to the 'object'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="objectQuantity" type="thesu:objectQuantity" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectQuantity' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="objectMeasuresGroup" type="thesu:objectMeasuresGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectMeasuresGroup'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="productOf" type="thesu:productOf" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'productOf' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="objectFunction" type="thesu:objectFunction" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectFunction' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:originalObject" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'originalObject' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectQuantity">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify an object's reported or intended quantity in the context
        of a 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' (e.g. "3" for the object "iron bar" in the phase
        "two iron bars were being welded together"; "2 grams" for the object "borax" in "add borax,
        2 g, to the weld"; "3 liters" for the object "oil" in the phase "they usually immerse the
        incandescent steel in 3 liters of oil"; or "2 handfuls" for the object "lime" in "one must
        pour two handfuls of lime into the furnace"). The base quantity of the object can be
        specified as a number in '@number'. If a measurement unit is present (e.g. "gram",
        "handful", etc.), this can be specied in '@measurementUnit' via one or more tags, each
        expressed as an href to the URI of an authorized spelling in an authority record associated
        with the TheSu corpus (i.e. an authority record whose URI is referred to in an
        'authorityRecord' with '@objectDetailsTags' specified as "true"). In '@measurementType', it
        is possible to specify the kind of the present quantification (e.g. "count", "weight",
        "capacity", etc.) via one or more tags, each expressed as an href to the URI of an
        authorized spelling in an authority record associated with the TheSu corpus (i.e. an
        authority record whose URI is referred to in an 'authorityRecord' with '@objectDetailsTags'
        specified as "true"). If the quantification is approximative (e.g. "roughly a spoonful" or
        "just enough"), '@approximative' may be specified as "true". If the quantification is not
        numerical (e.g. "as required", or "as much as they like"), '@number' should not be provided
        with a value, and the non-numerical quantification should be reported as a string in
        '@nonNumerical'. If the quantification is relative to any attribute of other objects (e.g.
        the object "bloom to be smelted" for the quantity "1 handful" in the phase "one must pour
        lime into the furnace, roughly a handful for each kilogram of the inserted bloom", or even
        objects otherwise unrelated to the described process, as in "prepare salt matching the
        weight of three coins"), any number of such objects may be referenced in 'relativeTo'. If
        the full quantification combines a base quantity with any number of additional quantities
        (e.g. in the phase "add borax, 2 g, to the weld, plus 1 g for each additional 5 cm of iron
        surface", or in the succession "they usually immerse the incandescent steel in 3 liters of
        oil, and then increase the latter by 0.5 liter"), each of such additional quantities may be
        added in 'quantityAddition' (note that for repeated objects it is also possible to not
        specify any base quantity, and only annotate the additions, as would be required in the
        succession "they usually immerse the incandescent steel in 3 liters of oil, and then
        increase the latter by 0.5 liter", where the second phase re-employs the "oil" of the first
        while increasing its quantity). If the object is involved in a phase within a 'sequence'
        contained in a 'THESIS', and the object's quantification reported or intended by the
        'THESIS''s speakers or authors, as conveyed by the full discourse or macrotext this is
        included in, is notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". If the object is
        plural but the quantity is left totally unspecified (e.g. "jars" in "lead is placed over
        vinegar in jarss"), '@unspecifiedPlurality' may be specified as "true". The annotator may
        prove that the object is quantified in the specified way via 'proof', by referring to
        textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding
        to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source') of the overall quantification. Since the annotator's interpretation of the
        object's quantity can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be
        added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="relativeTo" type="thesu:object" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which an object's reported or intended base
            quantity is relative to any number of other objects (e.g. the quantity "1 handful" as
            related to the object "bloom to be smelted" in the phase "one must pour lime into the
            furnace, roughly a handful for each kilogram of the inserted bloom"). Since 'relativeTo'
            elements are annotated exactly like 'object' elements, refer to the 'object' complexType
            for instructions. Definition to be extended and improved.
            <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:quantityAddition" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation/>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:attribute>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:measurementUnit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:measurementType"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:unspecifiedPlurality"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via '@ref' in the form of an href, to an already annotated
        'object' involved in a 'sequence'. For 'objectRef' elements annotated within a 'sequence'
        contained in a 'THESIS', the annotator may prove that the referenced 'object' is relevant to
        the element employing the current 'objectRef' by using 'proof' and referring to pertinent
        textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding
        to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source'). Since the annotator's identification of the relevant 'object' in the context of
        the current 'objectRef' can be open to debate, references to secondary literature may be
        added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectRefsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate any number of references to 'object' elements relevant
        to the parent element. Add an 'objectRef' to reference each of these relevant objects. If
        the identification of the relevant objects is notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be
        specified as "true".</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="objectRef" type="thesu:objectRef" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="objectsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify any number of objects or ingredients involved in a
        'phase' annotated within a 'sequence', while possibly also providing details on the objects'
        functions, quantites, measures, and relation with preceding phases of the same sequence
        (e.g., whether they are the product of events or actions annotated in preceding phases). Add
        an 'object' for each distinct object or ingredient. Note that objects resulting from the
        combination or mixing of originally distinct objects in previous phases can qualify as new
        individual objects.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="object" type="thesu:object" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'object' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="omittedElements">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify that certain relevant THESIS, MISC, or SUPPORT elements
        have been omitted from the annotation. The '@number' attribute may be used to specify the
        exact quantity of omitted elements, including when only a single element is omitted (by
        setting '@number="1"'). If the '@number' attribute is not provided, the quantity is
        considered unspecified, indicating that one or more elements may have been omitted without
        committing to an exact count.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="omissions">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to record discourse components that in the source text are relevant
        to this element's ancestor 'SUPPORT' but have been omitted from the analysis. If one or more
        theses have been omitted, use 'omittedTHESES'. If one or more MISC elements have been
        omitted, use 'omittedMISCS'. For each omitted set of supports sharing exactly the same
        function (including sets of only one support) that have been omitted, use a separate
        'omittedSUPPORTS' element. In each 'omittedSUPPORTS' element, the relevant functions
        (argumentation, exposition, expansion, and/or contextualization) can be detailed with
        dedicated attributes. It is also possible to leave this element empty (without children
        elements) to indicate the presence of omissions without specifying their exact
        type.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:omittedTHESES" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:omittedMISCS" minOccurs="0"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:omittedSUPPORTS" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0"/>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="paraphrasis" mixed="true">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide a clear and concise paraphrasis, in the language that has
        been chosen for the TheSu corpus, either of the semantic content of a 'PROPOSITION',
        'THESIS', 'SUPPORT', or 'MISC', or of a portion of their semantic content associated with
        one of their descendant elements, in the free form of a string. The paraphrasis must always
        be consistent with all the details specified by the annotator within the pertinent element
        (e.g. the '@polarity' of 'PROPOSITION' or 'THESIS' elements and all the information
        specified in 'propositionType' or 'thesisType'; for 'SUPPORT' elements, the information
        specified in 'supportType'; for 'phase' elements, any of its associated objects in
        'objectsGroup' and details related to timing in 'phaseTemporality'; etc.). When the
        'paraphrasis' is contained in a 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' element, or in any of their
        descendants, it is always representative of the annotator's interpretation of the text
        associated with its parent element. In the case of 'MISC' elements, the paraphrasis may
        rather take the form of a short recapitulation (in accordance with the other details
        annotated in the same 'MISC') of a text portion, and represents as well the annotator's own
        understanding of it. For paraphrases included in 'THESIS', 'SUPPORT', or 'MISC' elements, or
        in any of their descendants, the annotator can prove the correctness of any details of the
        specified interpretation by using 'proof' and referring to textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') supporting it. In
        the case the interpretation is notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true".
        Since it can be open to debate, references to secondary literature may be added through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="paraphrasisSimple" mixed="true">

    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide a clear and concise paraphrasis, in the language that has
        been chosen for the TheSu corpus, of a portion of the semantic content of a 'THESIS',
        'MISC', 'SUPPORT', or 'PROPOSITION' associated with one of their descendant elements, in the
        free form of a string. The paraphrasis must always be consistent with all the details
        specified by the annotator within the pertinent element. For elements contained in 'THESIS',
        'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' elements, the paraphrasis is representative of the annotator's
        interpretation of their corresponding text.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phase">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a new phase in a sequence, along with details such as
        the objects or ingredients involved in it, or its duration. Every phase must be associated
        with a text or element corresponding to it. If the 'phase' is part of a 'sequence' contained
        in an "explicit" 'THESIS' element, the annotator may: refer to the exact segments of text
        &#8212;in the limits of the 'THESIS''s 'text'&#8212; that correspond to the current phase
        (including its subjects or objects mentioned in other phases, e.g. in the sentence "one must
        take the steel and bring it to red-yellow incandescence" the text of the second phase will
        correspond to "the steel... bring it to red-yellow incandescence") via 'textRef' (note that
        in this case the keywords corresponding to the text span will be assumed to be relevant to
        the current 'phase', and not to the others which do not refer to it); or again refer to the
        exact segments of text that correspond to the current phase (including its subjects or
        objects mentioned in other phases) but also provide them with their own micro-thematic
        annotation, via 'microThemedTextRef' (which is useful when the annotator needs to specify
        the relevant narrow themes of a phase without presenting them as central to the whole
        sequence or thesis, i.e. without specifying them in the 'thesisType''s child
        'microThemesGroup'); or refer to another annotated 'THESIS' or 'MISC' &#8212;figuring in its
        whole as a phase in the current sequence&#8212; via 'elementRef' (this may be useful e.g. to
        connect in a unitary 'sequence' a large number of historical claims part of a cohesive
        narrative, but individually annotated as 'THESIS' elements); or freely type in the span of
        text corresponding to the phase (including its subjects or objects mentioned in other
        phases) as it is specified in the 'paraphrasis' of the 'THESIS' (which is especially useful
        when the phase includes implicit keywords, not corresponding to any segment of text), and
        again, possibly, provide it with its own micro-thematic annotation, via
        'microThemedFreeText' (note that in this case the keywords corresponding to the text span of
        the 'paraphrasis' will be assumed to be relevant to the current 'phase', and not to the
        others which do not refer to it). If the 'phase' is part of a 'sequence' contained in an
        "implicit" 'THESIS' element, the annotator may: refer to another annotated 'THESIS' or
        'MISC' &#8212;figuring in its whole as a phase in the current sequence&#8212; via
        'elementRef' (this may be useful e.g. to connect in a unitary 'sequence' a large number of
        historical claims part of a cohesive narrative, but individually annotated as 'THESIS'
        elements); or freely type in the span of text corresponding to the phase (including its
        subjects or objects mentioned in other phases) as it is specified in the 'paraphrasis' of
        the 'THESIS' (which is especially useful when the phase includes implicit keywords, not
        corresponding to any segment of text), and possibly provide it with its own micro-thematic
        annotation (which is useful when the annotator needs to specify the relevant narrow themes
        of a phase without presenting them as central to the whole sequence or thesis, i.e. without
        specifying them in the 'thesisType''s child 'microThemesGroup'), via 'microThemedFreeText'
        (note that in this case the keywords corresponding to the text span of the 'paraphrasis'
        will be assumed to be relevant to the current 'phase', and not to the others which do not
        refer to it) If the 'phase' is part of a 'sequence' contained in a 'PROPOSITION' element,
        the annotator may: refer to another annotated 'PROPOSITION' &#8212;figuring in its whole as
        a phase in the current sequence&#8212; via 'elementRef' (this may be useful e.g. to connect
        in a unitary 'sequence' a large number of "historical" 'PROPOSITION' elements that need to
        be linked in a cohesive narrative); or freely type in the span of text corresponding to the
        phase (including its subjects or objects mentioned in other phases) as it is specified in
        the 'paraphrasis' of the 'PROPOSITION', and possibly provide it with its own micro-thematic
        annotation, via 'microThemedFreeText' (in this case, the annotator will be able to specify
        the relevant narrow themes of the current phase without presenting them as central to the
        whole sequence or proposition, i.e. without specifying them in the 'propositionType''s child
        'microThemesGroup' &#8212; also note that in this case the keywords corresponding to the
        text span of the 'paraphrasis' will be assumed to be relevant to the current 'phase', and
        not to the others which do not refer to it). For 'phase' elements within a 'sequence'
        contained in a 'THESIS', after a text or element has been associated with the 'phase', it is
        also possible to specify whether this phase is explicitly presented in the text as a
        distinct part of the 'sequence', at its specific insertion point, or only inferred by the
        annotator to be intended as such by the sequence's speakers or authors, and conveyed
        implicitly by their discourse: in the latter case, the annotator should not only specify
        '@implicit' as "true", but also prove that the sequence's speakers or authors intend that
        phase to be a distinct part of the 'sequence' it has been included in at its specific
        insertion point. For this purpose, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to pertinent
        textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding
        to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source'). Since the annotator's understanding of the existence, delimitation, and
        collocation of the phase can be open to debate, references to secondary literature may be
        added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'; the neutral 'externalRef'
        can be also added to 'phase' elements contained in 'PROPOSITION' elements. Concerning the
        phase's collocation in the succession, note that it will be assumed that the current 'phase'
        follows chronologically either on the phase annotated as its preceding 'phase' sibling or
        &#8211;if the current phase is the first of a 'phasesGroup'&#8211; on the last phase of the
        'phasesGroup' that precedes it in the same 'sequence' (if present). If this is not the case,
        and there is a jump or return at the current point of the sequence, the annotator may use
        'follows' to specify which phase of the overall 'sequence' the current phase chronologically
        comes next (and, for 'phase' elements contained in 'THESIS' elements, provide evidence of or
        references on such jump or return inside the 'follows' element). In the case the current
        'phase' is contained in a procedural 'sequence' (i.e. recipe or set of instructions), there
        is a possibility that it corresponds to the purpose (or one of the purposes) of the overall
        sequence (e.g. a phase "now you have hardened steel", or an introductory phrase "to have
        hardened steel" opening the recipe, artificially annotated as the final phase of the
        'sequence' corresponding to that recipe). If this is the case, the annotator should set as
        "true" the '@value' of 'containsPurpose'. Consequently, the current 'phase' will be assumed
        to be the result and purpose (or one of the results and purposes) of all the phases that
        preced it (including the phases contained in the other 'phasesGroup' elements). Details
        related to the timing of the current phase, such as the moment in time at which it begins or
        should begin, its duration, or the number of times it is reported or intended to be repeated
        (or the extent of the period of its repetitions), may be specified in 'phaseTemporality'.
        Furthermore, it is possible to specify any number of objects or ingredients involved in the
        current phase using 'objectsGroup', while possibly also providing details on the objects'
        functions, quantites, measures, and relation with preceding phases of the same sequence
        (e.g., whether they are the product of events or actions annotated in preceding phases). The
        annotator may also provide a clear and concise presentation, in the language that has been
        chosen for the TheSu corpus, of the current phase in 'paraphrasis', consistently with the
        semantic content of the 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' it is included in and with all the details
        specified in its children elements. In the case the current 'phase''s ancestor 'THESIS' has
        been connected to another 'THESIS' (or 'SUPPORT' targeting a 'THESIS') in a relationship of
        entailment or faithful re-elaboration via 'entailment' &#8594; 'entailedBy', and the thus
        referenced 'THESIS' (or 'THESIS' targeted by the referenced 'SUPPORT') contains a sequence
        taken by the annotator as equivalent to the current &#8212; either in meaning or in its
        implications &#8212; although different in its wording (e.g. when the sequence of the
        referenced 'THESIS' is "one must take the gray and make it red-yellow, and then immerse it
        in the white", and the sequence of the current 'THESIS', clarifying it, is "one must take
        the steel and bring it to red-yellow incandescence, and then immerse it in clean water"; or
        when the sequence of the referenced 'THESIS' is "the river flows into the sea after
        traversing rocky regions", and the sequence of the current 'THESIS', logically entailed by
        the former, is "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater after having been in
        contact with rocks"), the annotator may have decided to reference that same 'THESIS''s
        sequence by which the current 'phase''s ancestor sequence is taken to be entailed using
        'sequence' &#8594; 'correspondingThesisSequence'. After doing this, the annotator may also
        link the current 'phase' to the other sequence's specific phase or range of phases by which
        it is entailed via 'correspondingPhases', which also allows to specify subtle divergences in
        the way it is corresponded. Finally, in the case the current 'phase''s ancestor 'THESIS' has
        been connected to a corresponding 'PROPOSITION' via a 'matchingPropositionsGroup' &#8594;
        'matchingProposition', and this 'PROPOSITION' includes a 'sequence' matching the current
        sequence in propositional terms, the annotator may have decided to reference that same
        'PROPOSITION''s sequence via 'matchingPropositionSequence', thus connecting the current
        'THESIS''s 'sequence' to its propositional version. After doing this, the annotator may also
        link the current 'phase' to the other sequence's specific phase or range of phases by which
        it is entailed via 'correspondingPhases', which also allows to specify subtle divergences in
        the way it is corresponded. Finally, in the case the current 'phase''s ancestor 'THESIS' has
        been connected to at least one corresponding 'PROPOSITION' via a 'matchingPropositionsGroup'
        &#8594; 'matchingProposition', and this 'PROPOSITION' includes at least one 'sequence'
        matching the current sequence in propositional terms, the annotator may have decided to
        reference that same 'PROPOSITION''s sequence via 'matchingPropositionSequence', thus
        connecting the current 'THESIS''s 'sequence' to its propositional version. After doing this,
        the annotator may also link the current 'phase' to the other sequence's specific phase or
        range of phases whose contents match it via 'matchingPropositionPhases', which also allows
        to specify subtle divergences in the way it is matched. Multiple 'matchingPropositionPhases'
        elements can be added to the same 'phase'. If this happens, the ancestor 'sequence' must
        also contain multiple 'matchingPropositionSequence' elements, so that their positional order
        can be assumed to establish a mapping relationship. That is, the first
        'matchingPropositionPhases' element in order of appearence must corresponds to the first
        'matchingPropositionSequence' in the ancestor 'sequence', the second to the second, and so
        on. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:matchingPropositionPhases" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:correspondingPhases" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:choice>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:textRef"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:microThemedTextRef"/>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="microThemedFreeText" type="thesu:microThemedFreeText">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemedFreeText'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:choice>
      <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="follows" type="thesu:follows" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation> Please, refer to the 'follows' complexType. </xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="phaseTemporality" type="thesu:phaseTemporality" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseTemporality' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="objectsGroup" type="thesu:objectsGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectsGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="containsPurpose" type="thesu:containsPurpose" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'containsPurpose' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit" default="false"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseDuration">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --> Represents the duration of a phase.
        The number attribute can express different types of durations using special syntax: - "10" =
        exactly 10 - "-10" = up to 10 (maximum) - "10-" = at least 10 (minimum) - "7-10" = range
        from 7 to 10 </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:durationAddition" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element name="relativeEnd" type="thesu:phaseDurationRelativeEnd" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseDurationRelativeEnd'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:durationRange"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:momentInTime"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseDurationRelativeEnd">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexContent>
      <xs:restriction base="thesu:relativeToPhases">
        <xs:sequence>
          <xs:choice>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:fullyThemedTextRef"/>
            <xs:element name="fullyThemedFreeText" type="thesu:fullyThemedFreeText">
              <xs:annotation>
                <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'fullyThemedFreeText'
                  complexType.</xs:documentation>
              </xs:annotation>
            </xs:element>
          </xs:choice>
          <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        </xs:sequence>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:eventParaphrasis"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:when"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
      </xs:restriction>
    </xs:complexContent>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseRepetition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:repetitionsAddition" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element name="relativeEnd" type="thesu:phaseRepetitionRelativeEnd" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseRepetitionRelativeEnd'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:repetitionsRange"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:momentInTime"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseRepetitionRelativeEnd">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexContent>
      <xs:restriction base="thesu:relativeToPhases">
        <xs:sequence>
          <xs:choice>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:fullyThemedTextRef"/>
            <xs:element name="fullyThemedFreeText" type="thesu:fullyThemedFreeText">
              <xs:annotation>
                <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'fullyThemedFreeText'
                  complexType.</xs:documentation>
              </xs:annotation>
            </xs:element>
          </xs:choice>
          <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        </xs:sequence>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:eventParaphrasis"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:when"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
      </xs:restriction>
    </xs:complexContent>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseStart">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the moment in time at which a phase annotated within a
        'sequence' is reported or intended to begin. The start time may be either absolute (e.g. "in
        March 15", "at the winter equinox", etc.), relative to the occurrence or development of
        certain actions or events corresponding or not corresponding to other phases within the same
        sequence (e.g. "after it has boiled for 7 minutes", or "1 month before the vintage"), or
        both (e.g. "in mid-summer, after the fruits have ripened"). An absolute start time can be
        specified in '@momentInTime' in the free form of a string, following a consistent standard
        of numerical presentation (e.g. "March 15" may be specified as "03-15"), along with its
        narrower time unit (e.g. "UTC calendar day" for "03-15") being specified in '@timeUnit' via
        one or more tags, each expressed as an href to the URI of an authorized spelling in an
        authority record associated with the TheSu corpus (i.e. an authority record whose URI is
        referred to in an 'authorityRecord' with '@timeUnitTags' specified as "true"); if the
        absolute start time cannot be directly reduced to a numerical presentation (e.g. "at
        sunset", "in the cold season", "after a while", etc.), '@momentInTime' should not be
        provided with a value, and the timing should be reported as a string in '@nonNumerical'. In
        any case, if the absolute start time is approximative (e.g. "around March 15", "a few weeks
        before the vintage", "after a while", etc.), '@approximative' may be specified as "true". It
        is possible to specify a relative start time, and reference the actions or events on which
        it depends, whether corresponding or not to other phases annotated within the same sequence,
        using 'relativeTo'. If the current phase is annotated within a 'sequence' contained in a
        'THESIS', and the phase's start time reported or intended by the 'THESIS''s speakers or
        authors, as conveyed by the full discourse or macrotext this is included in, is notably
        uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". The annotator may prove that the start
        time corresponds to the one specified via 'proof', by referring to pertinent textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source'). Since the annotator's interpretation of the phase's reported or intended start
        time can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature,
        through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="relativeTo" type="thesu:phaseStartRelativeTo" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseStartRelativeTo'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:durationRange"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timingRelation"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:momentInTime"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseStartRelativeTo">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexContent>
      <xs:restriction base="thesu:relativeToPhases">
        <xs:sequence>
          <xs:choice>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:fullyThemedTextRef"/>
            <xs:element name="fullyThemedFreeText" type="thesu:fullyThemedFreeText">
