  <xs:complexType name="phasesGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a succession of one or more phases that are either part
        of a 'sequence' or &#8212; if at least two &#8212; constitute a 'sequence' in its entirety,
        along with details on each phase (involved objects or ingredients, duration, etc.). To add
        the individual phases, the annotator may use either 'newPhases' or 'repeatedPhases'. Note
        that in the case of procedural sequences (i.e. recipes or sets of instructions), any number
        of 'phase' and 'repeatedPhases' elements can be specified to contain the purpose of the
        procedure as a whole (e.g. an expected product, as in "now you have hardened steel", or in
        an introductory phrase "to have hardened steel" opening a recipe, which may be artificially
        annotated as the final phase of a 'sequence' corresponding to that recipe), using their
        child element 'containsPurpose'; when the purpose of a procedural sequence is known, the
        annotator should always specify at least one of its 'phase' or 'repeatedPhases' elements as
        containing the purpose of the overall sequence. If the current sequence is contained in a
        'PROPOSITION', or does not employ phases which have already been annotated in the same or in
        another 'sequence' &#8212; contained either in the current 'sequence''s own ancestor
        'THESIS' or in another of the same discourse or macrotext &#8212;, the annotator may specify
        them from scratch using 'newPhases'. If the sequence is contained in a 'THESIS', and does
        employ phases that have already been annotated in the same or in another 'sequence' &#8212;
        contained either in the current 'sequence''s own ancestor 'THESIS' or in another of the same
        discourse or macrotext &#8212;, the annotator may reference them using 'repeatedPhases'
        (useful e.g. when a range of steps in a procedure are meant to be repeated in the same
        procedure, or when a sequence is presented in a procedural text as a variant recipe of
        another, already annotated, recipe in the same text for the same product, or as a
        modification of another, already annotated, recipe in the same text resulting in a different
        product). For 'repeatedPhases', the annotator may also specify sub-groups of the referenced
        succession of phases that are skipped over at the current point of the sequence rather than
        repeated, using 'repeatedPhases''s child element 'exceptedPhases'. In normal cases, it is
        assumed that the broad theme of a succession of phases in any 'phasesGroup' matches the
        broad theme of the 'phasesGroup''s ancestor 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION', as specified in the
        latter's descendant 'macroThemesGroup'. For instance, if a 'THESIS' has been specified as
        "methodological", it will be assumed that all its 'phasesGroup' elements contain
        "methodological" phases, i.e. steps in a recipe or set of instructions; if a 'THESIS' has
        been specified as "physical" or "historical", it will instead be assumed that all its
        'phasesGroup' elements contain "physical" or "historical" phases, i.e. stages in a natural
        process or a historical succession of events. However, there are cases of sequences which
        combine prescriptions of steps with descriptions of events, or which mix broad themes in any
        other way (e.g. the sequence "to harden steel, one must heat it first; in the fire, it
        eventually becomes red-yellow: when this happens, one must immerse it in a cold liquid", is
        for the most part "methodological" in macro-theme, but includes a "physical" second phase).
        In such cases, the annotator may use the 'phasesGroup''s child 'macroThemesGroup' to specify
        the broad theme of its set of phases, inasmuch as it diverges from that of its ancestor
        'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' and that of its 'phasesGroup' siblings which do not contain
        'macroThemesGroup'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="macroThemesGroup" type="thesu:macroThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'macroThemesGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:choice>
        <xs:element name="newPhases" type="thesu:newPhases">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'newPhases' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="repeatedPhases" type="thesu:repeatedPhases">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'repeatedPhases' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:choice>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseTemporality">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify details related to the timing of a phase annotated within
        a 'sequence'. The moment in time at which the phase is reported or intended to begin can be
        specified in 'phaseStart'; the phase's reported or intended duration can be specified in
        'phaseDuration'; and the number of times the phase is described or intended to be repeated -
        or the extent of the period of its repetitions - can be specified in
        'phaseRepetition'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="phaseStart" type="thesu:phaseStart" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseStart' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="phaseDuration" type="thesu:phaseDuration" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseDuration' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="phaseRepetition" type="thesu:phaseRepetition" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseRepetition' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="phaseTemporalityChange">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="phaseStart" type="thesu:phaseStart" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseStart' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="phaseDuration" type="thesu:phaseDuration" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseDuration' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="phaseRepetition" type="thesu:phaseRepetition" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phaseRepetition' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="productOf">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which an object involved in a phase within a
        'sequence' is the product of events or actions annotated in preceding phases of the same
        'sequence', having the object been altered in those phases in any way including
        transformations, combinations with other ingredients, and removals of portions (note that
        every time the same object is involved in subsequent phases, but endures any alteration in
        the earlier phase, e.g. in the sequence "heat the steel in a furnace", "and then hammer it
        while it is still incandescent", in the later phase it should be always annotated as a
        'productOf' that earlier phase). It the current 'productOf''s parent element has been
        already identified with an earlier object through 'objectRef', this 'productOf' is used to
        specify alterations to that object. If the current 'productOf''s parent element has not been
        identified with an earlier object through 'objectRef', this 'productOf' is used to annotate
        a new object resulting from the events or actions annotated in earlier phases; in the latter
        case, if the new object's production is dependent on specific objects annotated in earlier
        phases, and not on others (e.g. as it results from the combination or mixture of certain
        specific objects), any number of such objects may be referenced in 'fromMultipleObjects'. In
        any case, all the last 'phasesGroup' or 'phase' elements whose annotated events or actions
        produce the current object should be referenced in '@phasesRef'; if this attribute is not
        provided with a value, it is assumed that the current object is produced as a result of the
        events or actions corresponding to the phase immediately preceding the current phase or
        range of phases within the same 'sequence'. To specify cumulatively what type of product the
        current object is, i.e. whether it is a combination of earlier objects, a mixture, a
        portion, or a transformation, the annotator may use 'productType'. If the current object
        results from removals of objects earlier included within it (e.g., in the succession "decant
        the wine in another vessel to separate it from the dregs, and then cover it by sealing the
        vessel", the same "wine" object is involved in both phases, but in the second it is the
        product of the removal of its "dregs" happening in the first phase), any number of such
        removed objects may be referenced in 'removedObjectsGroup'. If the current object is
        involved in a phase within a 'sequence' contained in a 'THESIS', and its causal relationship
        with the events or actions of the earlier phases reported or intended by the 'THESIS''s
        speakers or authors, as conveyed by the full discourse or macrotext this is included in, is
        notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". The annotator may prove that the
        object is indeed reported or intended to be produced as a result of the referenced phases
        via 'proof', by referring to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital
        source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the
        attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the annotator's interpretation
        of the object's relation to the earlier phases can be open to debate, it is also possible to
        add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="fromMultipleObjects" type="thesu:objectRefsGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which an object annotated as a 'productOf''s
            parent element &#8211; not already identified through 'objectRef' with a single object
            involved in an earlier phase within the same 'sequence' &#8211; corresponds to a new
            object whose production is dependent on specific objects annotated in earlier 'phase'
            elements, and not on others (e.g. as it results from the combination or mixture of
            certain specific objects). Add an 'objectRef' to reference each object involved in the
            constitution of the new object. Please, refer to the 'objectRefsGroup'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element name="productType" type="thesu:productType" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'productType' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="removedObjectsGroup" type="thesu:removedObjectsGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'removedObjectsGroup'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="productType">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, for an object produced as a result of events of actions
        annotated in earlier phases within the same 'sequence', what type of product that object is.
        If the object is produced as a result of the combination of other objects, specify
        '@combination' as "true"; if the object is produced as a result of a mixture of other
        objects, specify '@mixture' as "true"; if the object is identified as a portion being
        selected or extracted from itself or other objects, specify '@portion' as "true"; if the
        object is produced as a result of a transformation of itself or other objects, specify
        '@transformation' as "true". All these attributes can be specified as "true" cumulatively.
        If the object is involved in a phase within a 'sequence' contained in a 'THESIS', and its
        type of production reported or intended by the 'THESIS''s speakers or authors, as conveyed
        by the full discourse or macrotext this is included in, is notably uncertain, '@uncertain'
        may be specified as "true". The annotator may prove that the product's type corresponds to
        the one specified via 'proof', by referring to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the
        annotator's interpretation of the product's type can be open to debate, it is also possible
        to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:combination"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:mixture"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:portion"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:transformation"/>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="relativeToPhases">
