          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'removedObjects' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="segment">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer to a text segment in a digital source. The segment's
        beginning must be specified in '@from' in the form of an href to the URI of a point or
        segment in the text; if the segment is longer than its referenced beginning (e.g. longer
        than one word), its ending must be specified in '@to' in the same form. It is recommended to
        refer to IDs of single segments in an already parsed and annotated text (e.g. with a single
        'tei:seg' corresponding to each of its words). Positional references through xPointer may be
        unreliable on the long term, as the referenced digital source may be modified during or
        after the annotation (e.g. to correct OCR mistakes it).</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexContent>
      <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:from" use="required"/>
        <xs:attribute ref="thesu:to"/>
      </xs:restriction>
    </xs:complexContent>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="repeatedPhases">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to include in a sequence a succession of one or more phases which
        have already been annotated in the same or in another 'sequence' (contained either in the
        new 'sequence''s own ancestor 'THESIS' or in another of the same discourse or macrotext),
        and which are re-employed &#8212; possibly diverging on specific details &#8212; at the
        current point of the new sequence (e.g. because a range of steps in a procedure are meant to
        be repeated in the same procedure, or because a sequence is presented in a procedural text
        as a variant recipe of another, already annotated, recipe in the same text for the same
        product, or as a modification of another, already annotated, recipe in the same text
        resulting in a different product). To reference the full range of already annotated phases
        that are re-employed at the current point of the sequence, the annotator must first refer to
        the ID of the 'sequence' containing the 'phase' elements to which they correspond via
        '@sequenceRef'; if no value is specified for '@sequenceRef', it is assumed that the
        'sequence' containing the already annotated phases re-employed at the current point of the
        sequence is the same 'sequence' of which the current 'repeatedPhases' is a descendant: this
        'sequence' will thus count as "referenced sequence" for the current element. In absence of
        further specifications, it is assumed that all the phases of the referenced 'sequence' are
        re-employed at the current point of the sequence. If only a sub-range &#8212; whether
        continuous or discontinuous &#8212; of the phases of the referenced 'sequence' is here
        re-employed, the annotator must also use '@phasesRef' to reference the endpoints of the full
        range of 'phasesGroup' children of the same 'sequence', along with their 'phase'
        descendants, which are involved in the repetition. If the range of repeated phases is
        discontinuous, that is, the full range of phases referenced in '@sequenceRef' and
        '@phasesRef' also includes 'phase' elements that are not relevant to the current point of
        the sequence, the annotator may add an 'exceptedPhases' for each sub-range of phases which
        is skipped over at the current point of the sequence, to reference it while also specifying
        whether the exclusion is explicit in the text, and possibly also provide evidence of the
        exclusion. Note that the thus defined full range of repeated phases will be assumed to
        follow chronologically on the last phase of the 'phasesGroup' that precedes it in the same
        'sequence' (if present). If this is not the case, and there is a jump or return at the
        current point of the sequence, the annotator may use 'follows' to specify which phase of the
        overall 'sequence' the current range of 'repeatedPhases' chronologically comes next (and,
        for 'repeatedPhases' contained in 'THESIS' elements, provide evidence of or references on
        such jump or return inside the 'follows' element). In the case the current 'repeatedPhases'
        is contained in a procedural 'sequence' (i.e. recipe or set of instructions) intended by its
        speakers or authors as a variant of another annotated procedural 'sequence', and the purpose
        of the current sequence matches the purpose (or one of the purposes) of the original
        sequence (e.g. the purpose of both procedures is to make hardened steel), there is a
        possibility that the current sequence of referenced repeated phases includes a phase
        corresponding to the purpose (or one of the purposes) of the overall sequence (e.g. a phase
        "now you have hardened steel", or an introductory phrase "to have hardened steel" opening
        the recipe, artificially annotated as the final phase of the 'sequence' corresponding to
        that recipe). If this is the case, the annotator should set as "true" the '@value' of
        'containsPurpose'. Consequently, one phase of the current range of 'repeatedPhases' will be
        assumed to be the result and purpose (or one of the results and purposes) of all the phases
        that preced it (including the phases contained in the other 'phasesGroup' elements): if the
        referenced repeated phases of the original 'sequence' includes (or references, directly or
        indirectly) a 'phase' already specified as "containing the purpose", that phase will be
        identified as the one containing the purpose in the current 'repeatedPhases'; if, instead,
        the referenced repeated phases of the original 'sequence' does not include (or reference,
        directly or indirectly) a 'phase' already specified as "containing the purpose", it will be
        the final phase referenced in the current 'repeatedPhases' to be identified as the one
        containing the purpose. if the '@value' of 'containsPurpose' is set that the final phase
        referenced in the current 'repeatedPhases' is the result and purpose (or one of the results
        and purposes) of all the phases that preced it (including the phases contained in the other
        'phasesGroup' elements). Once the full range of re-employed phases has been referenced via
        '@sequenceRef', '@phasesRef' and 'exceptedPhases', it is also possible to specify whether
        the repetition of the referenced phases is explicitly communicated in the text corresponding
        to the current point of the sequence or only inferred by the annotator to be intended by the
        sequence's speakers or authors, and conveyed implicitly by their discourse: in the latter
        case, specify '@implicit' as "true". In either case, the annotator should prove that the
        sequence's speakers or authors intend the referenced phases to be re-employed at the current
        point of the sequence via 'proof', by referring to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the
        annotator's identification of the full range of repeated phases, along with the inference
        itself that phases are being re-employed at the current point of the sequence, can be open
        to debate, references to secondary literature may be added through 'externalRef',
        'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Note that the value of '@implicit' and the referenced
        'proof', as well as any scholarly reference, will be assumed to be related to the
        re-employment of each of the phases referenced in '@sequenceRef' and '@phasesRef'. If the
        full range of repeated phases includes explicitly re-employed phases along with implicitly
        re-employed phases, split the current 'repeatedPhases' into separate elements, children of
        consecutive 'phasesGroup' elements, separately referencing the explicitly re-employed phases
        and the implicitly re-employed phases. Similarly split the 'repeatedPhases' element for
        specificities in the application of 'proof, 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'
        to any sub-range of the total range of re-employed phases. Furthermore, note that it is also
        possible to reference in 'repeatedPhases' any phases that are re-employed at the current
        point of the sequence with divergences on specific details. In particular, if the
        re-employed phases, at the current point of the sequence, are presented or implied in the
        discourse to start at a different moment in time than originally, have a different duration,
        or be repeated in the process a different number of times, the annotator may specify these
        divergences for any number of referenced phases via 'changesInTemporalityGroup'.
        Additionally, if the re-employed phases, at the current point of the sequence, are presented
        or implied in the discourse to involve more or less objects than originally, or to involve
        certain objects with differences in specific details (such as the objects' quantity or
        function), the annotator may specify all such additions to, removals of, or alterations in
        the objects of any number of referenced phases via 'changesInObjectsGroup'. The annotator
        may also provide a clear and concise presentation, in the language that has been chosen for
        the TheSu corpus, of the entire succession of phases included in the current
        'repeatedPhases' in 'paraphrasis', consistently with the semantic content of the 'THESIS'
        they are included in and all their modifications specified in the current 'repeatedPhases'
        (if present). In the case the current 'repeatedPhases''s ancestor 'THESIS' has been
        connected to another 'THESIS' (or 'SUPPORT' targeting a 'THESIS') in a relationship of
        entailment or faithful re-elaboration via 'entailment' &#8594; 'entailedBy', and the thus
        referenced 'THESIS' (or 'THESIS' targeted by the referenced 'SUPPORT') contains a sequence
        taken by the annotator as equivalent to the current &#8212; either in meaning or in its
        implications &#8212; although different in its wording (e.g. when the sequence of the
        referenced 'THESIS' is "one must take the gray and make it red-yellow, and then immerse it
        in the white", and the sequence of the current 'THESIS', clarifying it, is "one must take
        the steel and bring it to red-yellow incandescence, and then immerse it in clean water"; or
        when the sequence of the referenced 'THESIS' is "the river flows into the sea after
        traversing rocky regions", and the sequence of the current 'THESIS', logically entailed by
        the former, is "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater after having been in
        contact with rocks"), the annotator may have decided to reference that same 'THESIS''s
        sequence by which the current 'repeatedPhases''s ancestor sequence is taken to be entailed
        using 'sequence' &#8594; 'correspondingThesisSequence'. After doing this, the annotator may
        also link the set of phases referenced in the current 'repeatedPhases' to the other
        sequence's specific range of phases by which they are entailed via 'correspondingPhases',
        which also allows to specify subtle divergences in the way they are corresponded. Finally,
        in the case the current 'repeatedPhases''s ancestor 'THESIS' has been connected to at least
        one corresponding 'PROPOSITION' via a 'matchingPropositionsGroup' &#8594;
        'matchingProposition', and this 'PROPOSITION' includes at least one 'sequence' matching the
        current sequence in propositional terms, the annotator may have decided to reference that
        same 'PROPOSITION''s sequence via 'matchingPropositionSequence', thus connecting the current
        'THESIS''s 'sequence' to its propositional version. After doing this, the annotator may also
        link the set of phases referenced in the current 'repeatedPhases' to the other sequence's
        specific range of phases whose contents match them via 'matchingPropositionPhases', which
        also allows to specify subtle divergences in the way they are matched. Multiple
        'matchingPropositionPhases' elements can be added to 'repeatedPhases'. If this happens, the
        ancestor 'sequence' must also contain multiple 'matchingPropositionSequence' elements, so
        that their positional order can be assumed to establish a mapping relationship. That is, the
        first 'matchingPropositionPhases' element in order of appearence must corresponds to the
        first 'matchingPropositionSequence' in the ancestor 'sequence', the second to the second,
        and so on. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:matchingPropositionPhases" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:correspondingPhases" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:exceptedPhases" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="follows" type="thesu:follows" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation> Please, refer to the 'follows' complexType. </xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="changesInTemporalityGroup" type="thesu:changesInTemporalityGroup"
        minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'changesInTemporalityGroup'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="changesInObjectsGroup" type="thesu:changesInObjectsGroup" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'changesInObjectsGroup'
            complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element name="containsPurpose" type="thesu:containsPurpose" minOccurs="0">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'containsPurpose' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:sequenceRef"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="sequence">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate the phases connected in an individual sequence, along
        with details on each phase (involved objects or ingredients, duration, etc.), that are part
        of the semantic content of a 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION'. A sequence can be a description of a
        chain of events (at least two, e.g. "the river flows into the sea after traversing rocky
        regions"), a reported or prescribed procedure (including recipes, e.g. "to harden steel, one
        must first bring it to incandescence and then immerse it in a cold liquid"), or a mix of the
        two (e.g. "to harden steel, one must heat it first; in the fire, it eventually becomes
        red-yellow: when this happens, one must immerse it in a cold liquid"). The sequence's phases
        must be annotated in the correct chronological succession &#8212; regardless of their
        original order of presentation &#8212; via one or more 'phasesGroup' elements (note that
        specified jumps and returns in the succession are allowed: see the element 'follows', child
        of 'phase' and 'repeatedPhases'). Each 'phasesGroup' can include either a sub-group of
        'newPhases', containing 'phase' elements, or a sub-group of 'repeatedPhases'. Note that in
        the case of procedural sequences (i.e. recipes or sets of instructions), any number of
        'phase' and 'repeatedPhases' elements can be specified to contain the purpose (or one of the
        purposes) of the procedure as a whole (e.g. an expected product, as in "now you have
        hardened steel", or in an introductory phrase "to have hardened steel" opening a recipe,
        which may be artificially annotated as the final phase of a 'sequence' corresponding to that
        recipe), using their child element 'containsPurpose'; when the purpose or purposes of a
        procedural sequence are known, the annotator should always specify at least one of its
        'phase' or 'repeatedPhases' elements as containing the purpose (or one of the purposes) of
        the overall sequence. In the case of 'sequence' elements contained in 'THESIS' elements, the
        division of phases in 'phasesGroup' elements, among other things, allows the annotator to
        avoid redundant annotation of phases which have already been annotated in the same or in
        other 'sequence' elements (contained either in the same or in another 'THESIS' of the same
        discourse or macrotext), and which are re-employed &#8212; possibly diverging on specific
        details &#8212; in the current sequence (such full or partial re-employment of phases or
        steps is especially common in procedural texts, e.g. a range of steps in a procedure are
        meant to be repeated in the same procedure, or when the text reports variant recipes for the
        same products, or modifications to recipes resulting in different products). Note that the
        'repeatedPhases''s child element 'exceptedPhases' also allows the annotator to specify
        sub-groups of each succession of repeated phases that are skipped over at the point in the
        sequence when the repetition occurs. The annotator can freely combine any number of
        'phasesGroup' elements containing 'newPhases' with others containing 'repeatedPhases', as
        long as the absolute succession of phases resulting from the combination of all
        'phasesGroup' elements, beginning with the first phase in the first 'phasesGroup' and ending
        with the last phase in the last 'phasesGroup', correctly captures the complete chronological
        succession (again, possibly employing 'follows' elements to specify jumps or returns in the
        succession). The 'sequence' can be given its own ID in '@xml:id'. This allows the annotator
        to refer to it in other 'sequence' elements, e.g. for the purpose of referencing in
        'repeatedPhases' any of its 'phasesGroup' elements and the phases they contain. There are
        other cases in which a 'sequence' may reference another 'sequence'. One of these is when the
        annotator interprets a sequence, inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse or
        macrotext this is included in, to be intended by its own speakers or authors as a variant,
        diverging account of another description (or part of another description) of the same
        process, or as an alternative, diverging procedure of a set of instructions (or part of a
        set of instructions) for the same purpose (or a similar one). In these cases, the annotator
        can use any number of 'maySubstitute' elements to reference the different sequences &#8212;
        either full sequences or parts of them &#8212; of which the current sequence is intended to
        be a variant or substitute. Another case in which a 'sequence' may reference another
        'sequence' is when it is included in a 'THESIS' that has been annotated as a faithful
        re-elaboration or direct logical derivation of another 'THESIS' containing a sequence taken
        by the annotator as equivalent to the current &#8212; either in meaning or in its
        implications &#8212; although different in its wording (e.g. when the sequence of the first
        'THESIS' is "one must take the gray and make it red-yellow, and then immerse it in the
        white", and the sequence of the second 'THESIS', clarifying it, is "one must take the steel
        and bring it to red-yellow incandescence, and then immerse it in clean water"; or when the
        sequence of the first 'THESIS' is "the river flows into the sea after traversing rocky
        regions", and the sequence of the second 'THESIS', logically entailed by the first, is "the
        river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater after having been in contact with rocks").
        Whenever the annotator wants to reference a 'sequence' matched in this way, it must be first
        ensured that this element's ancestor 'THESIS' includes, in 'entailment', an 'entailedBy'
        element correctly referencing the 'THESIS' (or 'SUPPORT' targeting the 'THESIS') containing
        the pertinent 'sequence', i.e. the 'sequence' that is taken to entail the current
        'sequence'; then, the annotator can add a 'correspondingThesisSequence' to reference that
        same 'THESIS''s sequence &#8212; either the full sequence or parts of it &#8212; by which
        the current sequence is taken to be entailed. After this, the annotator may individually
        link each 'phase' or range of phases in any of the current 'sequence''s descendant
        'newPhases' or 'repeatedPhases' to the other sequence's phases by which they are entailed,
        using these elements' descendants 'correspondingPhases'. Similar connections can be made
        among sequences and phases annotated in different 'PROPOSITION' elements, in the case one of
        these references the other in either in 'relationships' &#8594; 'entailment' or in
        'relationships' &#8594; 'similarity'. For this purpose, the annotator may use
        'correspondingPropositionSequence' in the same way as 'correspondingThesisSequence', and
        then proceed to link each 'phase' or range of phases to those of the related 'PROPOSITION'
        via 'correspondingPhases'. A final case in which this 'sequence' may reference another
        'sequence' is when its own ancestor 'THESIS' has been connected to a corresponding
        'PROPOSITION' via a 'matchingProposition' in 'matchingPropositionsGroup', and the
        corresponding 'PROPOSITION' includes a 'sequence' matching the current sequence in
        propositional terms. In such cases, the annotator may reference the 'sequence' contained in
        the 'PROPOSITION' via 'matchingPropositionSequence', thus connecting the 'THESIS''s
        'sequence' to its propositional version. Subsequently, the annotator may individually link
        each 'phase' in any of the former 'sequence''s descendant 'newPhases', or any
        'repeatedPhases' element, to the propositional 'phase' elements whose contents match them
        via their child element 'matchingPropositionPhases'. When multiple
        'matchingPropositionSequence' elements are included as children of a 'sequence', their
        ordinal position is assumed to establish a mapping relationship with the
        'matchingPropositionPhases' elements in the descendant 'phase' and 'repeatedPhases'
        elements. Specifically, the first 'matchingPropositionPhases' element in any descendant
        'phase' and 'repeatedPhases' maps to the first 'matchingPropositionSequence', the second to
        the second, and so on. This positional correspondence must be maintained for correct
        semantic interpretation across multiple referenced sequences. Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:correspondingPropositionSequence" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:matchingPropositionSequence" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:correspondingThesisSequence" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:maySubstitute" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      <xs:element name="phasesGroup" type="thesu:phasesGroup" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'phasesGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="sequencesGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>If a 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' includes sequences, each of these may be here
        analyzed in their phases, along with details on each phase (involved objects or ingredients,
        duration, etc.), via 'sequence'. A sequence can be a description of a chain of events (at
        least two, e.g. "the river flows into the sea after traversing rocky regions"), a reported
        or prescribed procedure (including recipes, e.g. "to harden steel, one must first bring it
        to incandescence and then immerse it in a cold liquid"), or a mix of the two (e.g. "to
        harden steel, one must heat it first; in the fire, it eventually becomes red-yellow: when
        this happens, one must immerse it in a cold liquid"). One 'sequence' may be added for each
        distinct process of these kinds, as present in the text of the corresponding 'THESIS' or
        'PROPOSITION'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="sequence" type="thesu:sequence" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'sequence' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="speakersGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer to the individuals or groups that are regarded to be the
        speakers of the statements or segments of text relevant to the parent element. For each of
        these speakers, the annotator must add a 'speaker'. If their identification is uncertain,
        '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". In the case the text is ambiguous enough to support
        an identification with more than one speaker or group of speakers, the annotator can decide
        to provide the details of all, but must choose one or more as the most likely to be the
        actual speakers by attributing to them a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the
        '@rank' in their corresponding 'speaker' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the
        others. When multiple 'speaker' elements are provided with the same rank, it is assumed that
        the annotator understands all of their corresponding individuals or groups to be the
        relevant speakers at the same time. In the case no 'speaker' element is provided with rank
        "1", it is assumed that the ambiguity is too high to propose a reasonable identification
        (but note that at least one alleged speaker, provided with rank "2", will still have to be
        favoured by the annotator). The annotator may prove the presence of such uncertainties via
        'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the ambiguity (note that this is not used as
        evidence for the ranking of the alleged speakers; this can be proven via the child element
        'proof' of each 'speaker'). Since the recognition of the ambiguity can be open to debate, it
        is also possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef',
        'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      <xs:element name="speaker" type="thesu:name" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'name' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>

  <xs:complexType name="textLocus">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide the coordinates of one or more segments of text that are
        relevant to the parent element, whether in the free form of a written reference or by
        linking to segments of text in a digital source. The annotator must use a 'locus' for each
        of such distinct segments of text. In the case the text is ambiguous enough to support the
        choice of more than one relevant locus or groups of loci, the annotator can decide to
        provide the coordinates of all, but must choose one or more as the most likely to be the
        truly relevant ones by attributing to them a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the
        '@rank' in their corresponding 'locus' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the
        others. When multiple 'locus' elements are provided with the same rank, it is assumed that
        the annotator understands all of their corresponding segments of text to be relevant at the
        same time. In the case no 'locus' element is provided with rank "1", it is assumed that the
        ambiguity is too high to propose a reasonable decision (but note that at least one relevant
        segment of text, provided with rank "2", will still have to be favoured by the annotator).
        The annotator may prove the presence of such uncertainties via 'proof', by referring to
        textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding
        to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source') of the ambiguity (note that this is not used as evidence for the ranking of the
        allegedly relevant segments of text; this can be proven via the child element 'proof' of
        each 'locus'). Since the recognition of the ambiguity can be open to debate, it is also
        possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="locus" type="thesu:locus" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:annotation>
          <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'locus' complexType.</xs:documentation>
        </xs:annotation>
      </xs:element>
      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
    </xs:sequence>
    <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
  </xs:complexType>



  <xs:simpleType name="freeText">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to store any text typed in the free form of a
        string.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:restriction base="xs:string"/>
  </xs:simpleType>

  <xs:simpleType name="rankType">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation> This defines the numerical ranking scale used to indicate the relative
        prominence of a function within a support element. The scale ranges from "1" (indicating the
        highest prominence) to "4" (indicating no specific relevance). Intermediate values "2" and
        "3" may be used when multiple functions are of note. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:restriction base="xs:integer">
      <xs:minInclusive value="1"/>
      <xs:maxInclusive value="4"/>
    </xs:restriction>
  </xs:simpleType>



  <xs:element name="AEsystem">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate the argumentative-expository system of a 'source'
        &#8212;i.e. the network of its theses and supports, connected in correspondence with their
        functional relations&#8212; and other TheSu elements based on its text. Any number of
        'THESIS', 'MISC', 'SUPPORT', 'keyword', and 'lectio' elements may be added in any order, but
        it is recommended that their succession reflects the succession of the beginnings of their
        corresponding text spans in the primary text associated with the 'source', to make the
        isolated TheSu document more easily readable for a human.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:choice minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
        <xs:element ref="thesu:THESIS" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:MISC" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:SUPPORT" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:keyword" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:lectio" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:choice>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="MISC">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate any span of text and provide it with similar details as
        those that are included in 'THESIS' elements, regardless of the text span's functionality or
        homogeneity of meaning; or to indicate the extent of a text span targeted by a
        non-argumentative support, in order to allow it to be referenced in one of the 'SUPPORT''s
        descendant 'target' elements; or to connect a text span to relevant secondary literature.
        Every 'MISC' must be given its own ID in '@xml:id', and associated with a span of the
        primary text which corresponds to the 'source' (i.e. the digital source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') via 'text'. The
        annotator may provide a clear and concise paraphrasis, in the language that has been chosen
        for the TheSu corpus, of the semantic content of a 'MISC' in 'paraphrasis', in a form that
        is coherent with all its other annotated details. When the associated text span is ambiguous
        enough to allow for multiple interpretations, and thus for the annotation of more than one
        distinct, mutually exclusive 'MISC' elements, all of these may be added to the TheSu
        document, but one of them will always have to be favoured by the annotator, and referred to
        by each of its alternative 'MISC' elements in their respective 'alternativeTo' children
        elements. For every 'MISC', one or more individuals or groups, presented in the text to be
        the speakers of the associated text span, can be specified in 'speakersGroup'; if the text
        span corresponds to a section, in its whole, towards whose claims the actual or full
        commitment of its speakers is generally limited (as its character is e.g. hyperbolic,
        joking, fictitious, etc.), such limitations can be specified in 'limitationsGroup'. The
        broad theme (e.g. "historical", "axiological", etc.) of the annotated text span can be
        specified in 'macroThemesGroup'; to specify the theme in more detail (e.g. "military",
        "psychological", etc.) 'microThemesGroup' may be used. Any of the words composing the
        semantic content of the 'MISC' &#8212;both those that are explicit in the text span referred
        to in 'text' and those that are implicit and inserted in its 'paraphrasis'&#8212; can be
        annotated as keywords in 'keywordsGroup' by referring to corresponding, separately-annotated
        'keyword' elements. If the annotated text span includes metaphors, details on their
        structure, meaning, and status may be annotated in 'metaphorsGroup'. In the case the
        annotated text span includes references passages in a text &#8212;whether in the same work
        or in another&#8212;, the annotator may provide links to such passages, the coordinates of
        their loci, or links to their corresponding TheSu elements (if any) in 'includedRefsGroup'.
        References to secondary literature commenting on the annotated text span can be included via
        'externalRef' elements. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:includedRefsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="speakersGroup" type="thesu:speakersGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'speakersGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:limitationsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="macroThemesGroup" type="thesu:macroThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'macroThemesGroup'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemesGroup">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element name="microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme'
                        complexType.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                    <xs:complexType>
                      <xs:complexContent>
                        <xs:restriction base="thesu:microTheme">
                          <xs:sequence>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
                            <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"
                              maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                          </xs:sequence>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
                        </xs:restriction>
                      </xs:complexContent>
                    </xs:complexType>
                  </xs:element>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="keywordsGroup" type="thesu:keywordsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphorsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:text"/>
        <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="externalRef" type="thesu:externalRef" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'externalRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:alternativeTo" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:doubleChecked"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="PROPOSITION">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>A proposition is the abstract, semantic content of a declarative sentence,
        i.e. the uninstantiated version of a thesis, which is synonymous (enough) with it. The
        element 'PROPOSITION' is used to connect between them, by means of their common reference in
        'matchingProposition', multiple 'THESIS' elements that are recognized by the annotator to be
        synonymous or very similar in meaning. Every 'PROPOSITION' must be given its own ID in
        '@xml:id', and also provided with a 'paraphrasis' describing its meaning, since none is
        linked to a text span in a work. The affirmative or negative character of the proposition
        may be specified in '@polarity'. Each 'PROPOSITION' can also be connected to other
        'PROPOSITION' elements whose meanings are e.g. logically equivalent, similar, or opposed to
        theirs by using 'relationships'. Further formal, structural, and thematic annotation may be
        added in 'propositionType'. The annotator may use 'externalRef' to refer to secondary
        literature of any kind concerning the present proposition (e.g. historical accounts of
        philosophers claiming it, current scientific confutations of it, etc.). Custom elements can
        be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:relationships" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:propositionType"/>
        <xs:element name="paraphrasis">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType mixed="true">
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:paraphrasis">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="externalRef" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>This is to refer to secondary literature of any kind concerning the
              present proposition (e.g. historical accounts of philosophers claiming it, current
              scientific confutations of it, etc.). Please refer to the 'externalRef'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:externalRef">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element ref="thesu:biblQuote" minOccurs="0"/>
                  <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis" minOccurs="0">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis'
                        complexType.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                  </xs:element>
                  <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:bibliographyRef"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:biblLocusRefFrom"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:biblLocusRefTo"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:biblLocusFree"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit" default="false"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:extrinsic" default="false"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:uncertain" default="false"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:polarity"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:doubleChecked"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="SUPPORT">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation> A support is a segment of text that is presented by its speaker in function
        of a part of the discourse that is conveyed by the same text. A support can be:
        argumentative, when it provides justifications for the acceptance or rejection of a thesis
        or of another support; expository, when it explains more clearly, stylistically, or in depth
        the meaning of another segment of text containing theses or supports; expansive, when it
        expands on an information conveyed by a thesis, favouring a more complete knowledge and
        understanding of it (thus corresponding to an excursus); or contextualizing, when it
        contextualizes the interpretation and reception of another segment of text containing theses
        or supports. These four functions may be cumulative. Every 'SUPPORT' must be given its own
        ID in '@xml:id', associated with a span of the primary text which corresponds to the
        'source' (i.e. the digital source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this
        element's ancestor 'source') via 'text', and linked to one or more 'THESIS', 'MISC', or
        'SUPPORT' elements in 'targetsGroup', in correspondence with all the parts of the discourse
        they are supports of. Note that it is also allowed to omit the annotation of some or all
        targets, provided an 'omittedTargets' element is used within 'targetsGroup'. In the case of
        implicit supports (e.g. implicit arguments expressed by directly mentioning examples,
        without their cogency being made explicit), the attribute '@implicit' must be specified as
        "true", and the text span linked in 'text' used to provide all the possible evidence of the
        implicit presence of such supports at these referenced points of the discourse. If the
        presence of "implicit" supports in their corresponding text span is notably uncertain,
        '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". Since the recognition of their presence can be open
        to debate, references to secondary literature may be added through 'externalRef',
        'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'; the neutral 'externalRef' can be added to "extrinsic"
        supports too. If the support makes use of specific annotated elements of the discourse
        &#8212;occurring in the text span indicated to be its 'text'&#8212; in order to fulfill its
        functions (e.g. theses used as premises), these should be referred to in 'employedElements'.
        Note that it is allowed to omit the annotation of some or all employed elements, provided an
        'omittedEmployedElements' element is used within 'employedElements'. In the case of
        "explicit" supports, the annotator may refer to textual discourse markers signalling their
        presence and function in the discourse (e.g. "because", "namely", "therefore", "however",
        etc.) in 'marker'. It is also allowed to annotate supports that are neither explicit nor
        implicit, but recognized to be extraneous to the speakers' intent at a certain point of the
        text, and yet relevant to the annotation for any reason: for such 'SUPPORT' elements,
        '@extrinsic' must be specified as "true". The annotator may provide a clear and concise
        paraphrasis, in the language that has been chosen for the TheSu corpus, of the semantic
        content of a 'SUPPORT' in 'paraphrasis', in a form that is coherent with all the other
        annotated details; in the case of "implicit" and "extrinsic" theses, the 'paraphrasis' must
        be included necessarily, since the meaning of the referenced text will never be identical
        with that of the annotated support. When the passage is ambiguous enough to allow for
        multiple interpretations, and thus for the annotation of more than one distinct, mutually
        exclusive 'SUPPORT' elements, all of such supports may be added to the TheSu document, but
        one of them will always have to be favoured by the annotator, and referred to by each of its
        alternative supports in their respective 'alternativeTo' children elements. For each
        'SUPPORT', at least one individual or group, presented by the text to be its speaker, must
        be specified in 'speakersGroup'; in the case of non-dialogic works, the speakers of most
        supports &#8212;except those in quotations&#8212; will generally be identical with the
        work's authors. Since not every support is presented by its speakers with actual or full
        commitment (but some only provisionally, hypothetically, jokingly, etc.), and supports are
        sometimes expressed only to be attacked (e.g. expected counter-arguments), the annotator may
        provide details on the extension of their speakers' assent &#8212;as can be inferred by the
        associated text&#8212;, in 'assent'; if these speakers are distinct from the work's authors
        or from superordinate speakers reporting on the support, the assent of these latter may be
        also specified here. Details on the support's function (i.e. argumentative, expository,
        expansive, contextualizing) and form (e.g. deductive reasoning, analogy, etc.) may be added
        in 'supportType'. In the case the annotated support includes references passages in a text
        &#8212;whether in the same work or in another&#8212;, and these passages are neither among
        its targets nor among its employed elements, the annotator may provide links to such
        passages, the coordinates of their loci, or links to their corresponding TheSu elements (if
        any) in 'includedRefsGroup'. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:targetsGroup"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:marker"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:includedRefsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="speakersGroup" type="thesu:speakersGroup">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'speakersGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:assent"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:supportType"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:employedElements"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:text"/>
        <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:alternativeTo" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit" default="false"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:extrinsic" default="false"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:doubleChecked"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="THESIS">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>A thesis is an explicit or implicit instantiation of a single proposition in
        a text, i.e. a minimal declarative sentence representing the stance of its speakers,
        independently of the stance's character (e.g. definitive or temporary, or sincere or
        simulated). Every 'THESIS' must be given its own ID in '@xml:id', and associated with a span
        of the primary text which corresponds to the 'source' (i.e. the digital source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') via 'text'. In the
        case of implicit theses (e.g. implicit declarative sentences suggested by means of
        rhetorical questions), the attribute '@implicit' must be specified as "true", and the text
        span linked in 'text' used to provide all the possible evidence of the implicit presence of
        such theses at these referenced points of the discourse. If the presence of "implicit"
        theses in their corresponding text span is notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified
        as "true". Since the recognition of their presence can be open to debate, references to
        secondary literature may be added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra';
        the neutral 'externalRef' can be added to "extrinsic" theses too. When more than one
        semantically-distinct statements &#8212;with respects to their autonomous
        informativity&#8212; in syntactic continuity (e.g. "the sun sends us heat and light", which
        can be split in "the sun sends us heat" and "the sun sends us light" without changes in
        meaning) are recognized to share most of the features that will be specified in their
        annotation &#8212;i.e. all except some micro-themes and keywords&#8212;, the annotator may
        decide, for convenience, to include all of them in the same 'THESIS' element, thus creating
        an aggregate-thesis: in such cases, the number of the so-combined individual statements will
        have to be specified in '@quantity'. Each 'THESIS' element may be linked to the abstract
        propositions they are recognized to be instances of, i.e. synonymous with them or very
        similar in meaning, by referencing their corresponding 'PROPOSITION' elements in
        'matchingPropositionsGroup': this is used to connect between them, by means of their
        references to the same 'PROPOSITION' elements, all theses in one or more TheSu corpora that
        appear to be synonymous (enough) with each other. Each 'THESIS' can also be connected to
        other 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' elements that logically entail them in any way by using
        'entailment'. It is also allowed to annotate theses that are neither explicit nor implicit,
        but recognized to be extraneous to the speakers' intent at a certain point of the text, and
        yet relevant to the annotation for any reason: for such 'THESIS' elements, '@extrinsic' must
        be specified as "true". The affirmative or negative character of the thesis may be specified
        in '@polarity'. The annotator may provide a clear and concise paraphrasis, in the language
        that has been chosen for the TheSu corpus, of the semantic content of a 'THESIS' in
        'paraphrasis', in a form that is coherent with all the other annotated details; in the case
        of "implicit" and "extrinsic" theses, the 'paraphrasis' must be included necessarily, since
        the meaning of the referenced text will never be identical with that of the annotated
        thesis. When the passage is ambiguous enough to allow for multiple interpretations, and thus
        for the annotation of more than one distinct, mutually exclusive 'THESIS' elements, all of
        such theses may be added to the TheSu document, but one of them will always have to be
        favoured by the annotator, and referred to by each of its alternative theses in their
        respective 'alternativeTo' children elements. For each 'THESIS', at least one individual or
        group, presented by the text to be its speaker, must be specified in 'speakersGroup'; in the
        case of non-dialogic works, the speakers of most theses &#8212;except those in
        quotations&#8212; will generally be identical with the work's authors. Since not every
        thesis is presented by its speakers with actual or full commitment (but some only
        provisionally, hypothetically, jokingly, etc.), and theses are sometimes expressed only to
        be attacked, the annotator may provide details on the extension of their speakers' assent
        &#8212;as can be inferred by the associated text&#8212;, in 'assent'; if these speakers are
        distinct from the work's authors or from superordinate speakers reporting on the statement,
        the assent of these latter may be also specified here. Further formal, structural, thematic,
        and intertextual annotation may be added in 'thesisType'. In the case the annotated
        declarative sentence includes references passages in a text &#8212;whether in the same work
        or in another&#8212;, and these passages are not the objects of the present 'THESIS'
        &#8212;as either objects of a "metatext" or of a "historical" report&#8212;, the annotator
        may provide links to such passages, the coordinates of their loci, or links to their
        corresponding TheSu elements (if any) in 'includedRefsGroup'. Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:matchingPropositionsGroup"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:entailment" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:includedRefsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="speakersGroup" type="thesu:speakersGroup">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'speakersGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:assent"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:thesisType"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:text"/>
        <xs:element name="paraphrasis" type="thesu:paraphrasis">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'paraphrasis' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:alternativeTo" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:polarity" default="aff"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:quantity" default="1"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit" default="false"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:extrinsic" default="false"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:doubleChecked"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="TheSu">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is the root element of a TheSu corpus. The corpus can be given its own
        ID in '@xml:id'. The authority records listing all of the allowed spellings of the tags used
        in the corpus must be referenced in 'authorizedTags'. If the corpus includes any 'THESIS'
        element that the annotator intends to connect to 'PROPOSITION' elements, these 'PROPOSITION'
        elements must be included in 'propositions'. One or more 'source' elements must be added, in
        correspondence with each of the distinct primary texts that the annotator intends to
        annotate in the TheSu corpus.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:authorizedTags"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:propositions"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:source" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="alternativeTo">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via one or more 'elementRef' elements, to the 'THESIS',
        'MISC', 'SUPPORT', or 'keyword' elements a 'THESIS', 'MISC', 'SUPPORT', or 'keyword' is an
        alternative interpretation of in relation to its associated text, only in the case this
        element has not been chosen by the annotator as part of the likeliest interpretation. The
        only elements referred to via 'elementRef' must be the ones that have been chosen as part of
        the favoured interpretation. Since it is possible to include in the TheSu document more than
        one alternative interpretations to the favoured, the annotator may rank the likelyhood of
        each in '@rank', by using a number between "1" (likeliest alternative to the favoured
        interpretation) and "4" (less likely alternative to the favoured interpretation). When
        multiple "alternative" elements share the same rank, it is assumed that they are part of the
        same interpretation and would thus be valid at the same time, if their corresponding
        interpretation were the correct (note that each of these, in turn, may also be referenced by
        further "alternative" elements). Since the annotator's can be open to debate, it is also
        possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="ambiguous">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, through '@value', whether an annotated 'metaphor' in a
        'THESIS' or 'MISC' corresponds to a metaphor or metonymy that is meant by its speakers to be
        ditropically ambiguous &#8212;i.e. activating its metaphorical or metonymic sense (with
        respects to the same 'THESIS' or 'MISC') simultaneously with its literal meaning&#8212; or
        univocally a metaphor or metonymy (inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse it is
        included in). The annotator's choice may be supported, through 'proof', by referring to
        relevant textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not
        corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this
        element's ancestor 'source'). In the case the recognition of the ambiguity is notably
        uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". Since it can be open to debate,
        references to secondary literature may be added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:value"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="argumentation">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, in '@rank', how prominent is the argumentative function
        in a support with respects to the others, as indicated in the ranks of this element's
        siblings 'exposition', 'expansion', and 'contextualization'. If the chosen rank is higher
        than "4" &#8212;i.e. closer to "1"&#8212;, this means that the support is (also) used by its
        speakers to argue for or against the content of one or more 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' elements.
        The argument's aim towards its target must be specified in '@for' by using the following
        values: "acc" if the argument supports the acceptance of its target theses or supports;
        "rej" if it supports their rejection (and is therefore a refutation); or "mix" if it
        supports both their acceptance and rejection at the same time (rather examining or
        problematizing them). To prove the prominence that has been indicated for this function, the
        annotator may use 'proof' and refer to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital
        source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the
        attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the support's argumentative
        function. Since the annotator's interpretation can be open to debate, it is also possible to
        add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:for" default="acc"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank" default="4"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="assent">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide details on the extension of the assent of the speakers of
        a 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' towards the content of the same 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT', inasmuch as
        can be inferred from the full discourse this is included in, as well as on the assent of the
        work's authors (if distinct from these speakers) and of any superordinate speaker reporting
        on the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' without themselves committing to it. Information on the assent
        of the speakers of the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' can be annotated in 'assentSpeakers', in which
        it is also possible to specify the presence in the text of any limitations to the speakers'
        full commitment &#8212; i.e. signals that the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' should be understood as
        a weakened claim (e.g. "it is likely that..."), as hyperbolic, as humorous, as hypothetic
        and provisional, or as fictitious (note that these limitations may be cumulative). The
        assent of all superordinate speakers (if any) can be specified in 'assentSupSpeakersGroup';
        and the assent of the work's authors in 'assentAuthor'. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:assentSpeaker"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:assentSupSpeakersGroup"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:assentAuthor"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="assentAuthor">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the assent of the authors of the work containing this
        element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' towards its content, inasmuch as can be inferred
        from the full macrotext this is included in. The assent can be specified in '@assentValue'
        by using the following values: if the authors agree with the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' they
        report, choose "aff" (affirmative assent); if they do not agree with it, choose "neg"
        (negative assent); if they not only do not agree with it, but also refute it somewhere in
        the same macrotext, choose "att" (attack). If no value is specified, it is assumed that the
        authors' assent is indiscernible. If a value has been chosen, but the determination of the
        authors' assent is notably uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". The annotator's choice
        may be supported, through 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a
        digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in
        the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the indicated authors' assent.
        Since the annotator's choice can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to
        secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:assentValue"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="assentSpeaker">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide details on the extension of the assent of the speakers of
        this element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' towards the content of the same 'THESIS' or
        'SUPPORT', inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse this is included in. The
        assent can be specified in '@assentValue' by using the following values: if the speakers
        present the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' with positive commitment, choose "aff" (affirmative
        assent); if they present it without believing in it, choose "neg" (negative assent); if they
        not only do not believe in it, but also refute it shomewhere in the same discourse, choose
        "att" (attack). If no value is specified, it is assumed that the speakers' assent is
        indiscernible. If a value has been chosen, but the determination of the speakers' assent is
        notably uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". The annotator's choice may be supported,
        through 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the indicated speakers' assent. Since the
        annotator's choice can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. It is also possible,
        in 'limitationsGroup', to specify the presence in the text of any limitations to the
        speakers' full commitment towards the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' at the moment they make the
        claim &#8212; i.e. signals that the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' should be understood as a weakened
        claim (e.g. "it is likely that..."), as hyperbolic, as humorous, as hypothetic and
        provisional, or as fictitious (note that these limitations may be
        cumulative).</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:limitationsGroup"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:assentValue"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="assentSupSpeaker">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the assent of a superordinate speaker (whether individual
        or plural) reporting on this element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' &#8212;without
        themselves committing to it&#8212; towards the content of the same 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT',
        inasmuch as can be inferred from the full macrotext this is included in. The assent can be
        specified in '@assentValue' by using the following values: if the superordinate speakers
        agree with the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' they report, choose "aff" (affirmative assent); if they
        do not agree with it, choose "neg" (negative assent); if they not only do not agree with it,
        but also refute it somewhere in the same macrotext, choose "att" (attack). If no value is
        specified, it is assumed that the superordinate speakers' assent is indiscernible. If a
        value has been chosen, but the determination of the superordinate speakers' assent is
        notably uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". The annotator's choice may be supported,
        through 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the indicated superordinate speakers' assent.
        Since the annotator's choice can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to
        secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:assentValue"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="assentSupSpeakersGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via one or more 'assentSupSpeaker' elements, the assent
        of all superordinate speakers (if any) reporting on this element's ancestor 'THESIS' or
        'SUPPORT' &#8212;without themselves committing to it&#8212; towards the content of the same
        'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT', inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse this is included
        in. If the report of the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' is nested in another report (and so on), an
        'assentSupSpeaker' may be added for the superordinate speakers of each nested report; the
        order of succession of these elements must correspond to the order of the nested reports,
        from the inner to the outer &#8212; e.g. if a 'THESIS' from Gorgias is quoted by Protagoras
        in a speech that is reported by Socrates, the first 'assentSupSpeaker' of Gorgias's 'THESIS'
        will correspond to Protagoras's assent, and the second to Socrates's. All of the speakers
        matching the succession of 'assentSupSpeaker' elements must correspond to speakers
        associated with 'THESIS' or 'MISC' elements in which this element's ancestor 'THESIS' or
        'SUPPORT' is nested, i.e. 'THESIS' or 'MISC' elements of the "historical" or "metatextual"
        kind &#8212; e.g. the aforementioned 'THESIS' from Gorgias will have to be annotated as part
        of a "historical" or "metatextual" 'THESIS' or 'MISC' with Protagoras as its speaker, and
        this latter 'THESIS' or 'MISC' annotated as part of a "historical" or "metatextual" 'THESIS'
        or 'MISC' with Socrates as its speaker.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:sequence>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:assentSupSpeaker" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
            </xs:element>
          </xs:sequence>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="author">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'name' complexType. In the case the annotator (or any
        scholar) judges the attribution of the text to the specified author to be
        pseudoepigraphical, or considers this possibility or rejects it, this may be specified and
        connected with relevant literature in 'spurious'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:extension base="thesu:name">
          <xs:sequence>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:spurious"/>
          </xs:sequence>
        </xs:extension>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="authority">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide the details of an authority that is referenced in an
        argument from authority. In the case the authoritative information corresponds to a
        'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' in a TheSu document, the annotator may simply use
        'elementRef' to link to it. Otherwise, the annotator may specify the name or group
        designator of the authority in 'authorityName'. Then, in the case the argument from
        authority mentions or alludes to a specific text passage, the annotator may provide its
        coordinates (whether in the free form of a written reference or by linking to a text segment
        in a digital source) in 'authorityLocus'. To prove the relevance of the referenced element
        or name of authority and segment of text, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source')
        of the citation or allusion. Since the identification of the relevant authority can be open
        to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature, through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. The identification of the authority
        referenced in the argument from authority may sometimes be uncertain due to an ambiguity in
        the latter's phrasing: in such cases, the annotator may use '@rank' to specify how likely is
        each annotated 'authority' to be the truly relevant one with respect to its siblings, by
        giving it a value between "1" (most likely) and "4" (least likely). Custom elements can be
        added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="authorityName" type="thesu:speakersGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'speakersGroup' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="authorityLocus" type="thesu:textLocus" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'textLocus' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="authorityDetails">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This it to add further details in the case a 'supportForm' has been
        annotated as an argument from authority. To specify the name or group designator of each of
        the referenced authorities, along with the text passages mentioned or alluded to in the
        argument from authority (if any), the annotator may use an 'authority'. If their
        identification is uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". In the case the reference is
        ambiguous enough to support an identification with more than one authorities or groups of
        authorities, the annotator can decide to provide the details of all, but must choose one or
        more as the most likely to be the truly referenced ones by attributing to them a higher
        rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the '@rank' in their corresponding 'authority'
        elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the others. When multiple 'authority' elements
        are provided with the same rank, it is assumed that the annotator understands the argument
        from authority to refer to all their corresponding authorities at the same time. In the case
        no 'authority' element is provided with rank "1", this means that the ambiguity is too high
        to propose a reasonable identification (but note that at least one authority, provided with
        rank "2", will still have to be favoured by the annotator). The annotator may prove the
        presence of such uncertainties via 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the ambiguity
        (note that this is not used as evidence for the ranking of the authorities; this can be
        proven via the child element 'proof' of each 'authority'). Since the recognition of the
        ambiguity can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be
        added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:authority" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="authorityRecord">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This links through '@ref' to the URL of an authority record that is
        referenced by the tags in the corpus. An authority record can be referenced by one or more
        kinds of tags: if it contains the authorized spellings of the tags in '@bibliographyRef',
        specify '@bibliohraphyTags' as "true"; if '@entailedAs', '@entailmentTags'; if '@namely',
        '@keywordTags'; if '@formTag', '@formTags'; if '@historyTime' and '@historyType',
        '@historyTags'; if '@macroThemeTag', '@macroThemeTags'; if '@microThemeTag',
        '@microThemeTags'; if '@name', '@nameTags'; if '@opposedAs', '@oppositionTags'; if
        '@timeUnit', '@timeUnitTags'; if it contains the authorized spellings of the tags in
        '@measurementUnit' and '@measurementType', specify '@objectDetailsTags' as
        "true".</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref" use="required"> </xs:attribute>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:bibliographicRecords" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:entailmentTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:keywordTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:formTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:historyTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:macroThemeTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nameTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:oppositionTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:objectDetailsTags" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnitTags" default="false"/>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="authorizedTags">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to list the URLs of the authority records referenced in the corpus
        by the tags in: '@bibliographyRef', '@entailedAs', '@namely', '@formTag', '@historyTime',
        '@historyType', '@macroThemeTag', '@microThemeTag', '@name',
        '@opposedAs'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:authorityRecord" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="authorsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the authors of a primary text corresponding to a
        'source', whether certain, alleged, or merely hypothetical. For each of such authors, the
        annotator may add an 'author'. If their identification is uncertain, '@uncertain' may be
        specified as "true". In the case the uncertainties are such that the autorship of the text
        may be attributed to more than one author or group of authors, the annotator can decide to
        provide the details of all, but must choose one or more as the most likely to be the actual
        authors by attributing to them a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the '@rank' in
        their corresponding 'author' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the others. The
        annotator may prove the presence of such uncertainties via 'proof', by referring to textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source')
        of the ambiguity (note that this is not used as evidence for the ranking of the alleged
        authors; this can be proven via the child element 'proof' of each 'author'). Since the
        recognition of the ambiguity can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to
        secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. When
        multiple 'author' elements are provided with the same rank, it is assumed that the annotator
        understands all of their corresponding individuals or groups to share the authorship of the
        text. In the case no 'author' element is provided with rank "1", or the 'authorsGroup'
        includes no 'author' elements at all, it is assumed that the uncertainty is too high to
        propose a reasonable identification. In this circumstance, the text, rather than being
        associated with any specific author, is just taken to be anonymous, and the annotator may
        use 'anonymousNickname' to specify a name with which to refer to the anonymous author or
        group of authors (e.g. "Pseudo-Aristotle", "Anonymous of Canterbury",
        etc.).</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:author" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:anonymousNickname"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="bibliography">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to include information on the relevant bibliography on a 'source'.
        Any number of bibliographical references may be added via 'bibliographyRef' elements; in the
        case the source is a digital edition of a text &#8212;meaning that the primary text, rather
        than being identifiable with the digital source itself, is reported in it&#8212;, the
        annotator must provide a 'bibliographyRef' referred to its corresponding bibliographic
        record and specify it as the "base edition" for the 'source'. References to specific
        sections or passages in any work of secondary literature commenting on the source as a whole
        may be added via 'externalRef' elements. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:bibliographyRef" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="externalRef" type="thesu:externalRef" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>This is to refer to specific sections or passages of any work of
              secondary literature commenting on the primary text of a 'source' as a whole. Please
              refer to the 'externalRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="bibliographyRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via '@ref' in the form of an href, to a bibliographic
        record in the bibliography authority record associated with the TheSu document (i.e. whose
        URI is referred to in an 'authorityRecord' with '@bibliographicRecords' specified as "true".
        If a digital edition of the referenced work exists, its URI may be referred to in
        '@digitalEdition' in the form of an href. In the case the referenced work corresponds to the
        digital source associated with the 'source', and this is a digital edition of a text (i.e.
        it is not identifiable with the primary text itself, but reports it), 'baseEdition' must be
        specified as "true". If the referenced work is or contains a complete edition of the primary
        text corresponding to the 'source', 'completeEdition' may be specified as "true"; if it is
        or contains a collection of philological notes on the text, 'philologicalNotes' may be
        specified as true; if it is or contains a translation of the text, 'translation' may be
        specified as "true". Every 'bibliographyRef' can be provided with its own ID in '@xml:id':
        this allows the annotator to reference them &#8212;rather than their corresponding
        bibliographic records&#8212; in the 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'
        elements in the TheSu document, thus simplifying the annotation and shortening the
        links.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:digitalEdition"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:baseEdition" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:completeEdition" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:philologicalNotes" default="false"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:translation" default="false"/>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="biblQuote" type="xs:string">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to quote a relevant passage in a referenced work.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="originalObject">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="objectRef" type="thesu:objectRef">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'objectRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="conscious">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, through '@value', whether an annotated 'microTheme',
        'macroTheme', or 'metaphor' reflects the ideas or intentions of the speakers of its ancestor
        'THESIS' or 'MISC' or not; i.e. whether they are aware (inasmuch as can be inferred from the
        full discourse or macrotext that includes their statements) of its core annotated detail or
        not. The annotator's choice may be supported, through 'proof', by referring to relevant
        textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding
        to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source'). In the case of 'metaphor' elements, if the speakers of the 'THESIS' or 'MISC'
        that includes the corresponding metaphor or metoymy match any of speakers that have been
        indicated in 'metaphorRecognition' to be the ones manifesting to recognize its metaphorical
        or metoymical character (if any), and a text span has been associated with the annotation of
        their recognition, the use of 'proof' is here redundant and avoidable. In the case the
        recognition of the speakers' awareness is notably uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified
        as "true". Since it can be open to debate, references to secondary literature may be added
        through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:value"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="contextualization">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, in '@rank', how prominent is the contextualizing
        function in a support with respects to the others, as indicated in the ranks of this
        element's siblings 'argument', 'exposition', and 'expansion'. If the chosen rank is higher
        than "4" &#8212;i.e. closer to "1"&#8212;, this means that the support is (also) used by its
        speakers to contextualize the interpretation and reception of the content of one or more
        'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' elements. To prove the prominence that has been indicated for
        this function, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to textual evidence (i.e. text
        segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is
        referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the support's
        contextualizing function. Since the annotator's interpretation can be open to debate, it is
        also possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef',
        'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. In the case the targets of a "contextualizing" support
        are themselves used, by the same speakers, to contextualize the content of their own
        "contextualizing" support &#8212;i.e. the contents of multiple, reciprocal,
        "contextualizing" supports are presented in a symmetrical structure in which they are all
        equally rhematic and none thematic with respects to the others&#8212;, the annotator can
        avoid to annotate further "contextualizing" 'SUPPORT' elements for the reciprocating targets
        of the first "contextualizing" support, and just indicate that the contextualization is
        reciprocal by specifying "@reciprocal' as "true". This situation may occur, for instance,
        when a contextualizing support is used to introduce a contrast (e.g. the phrase "differently
        than the sun" in the sentence "differently than the sun, the moon radiates reflected
        light"), but the annotator recognizes the target of the contrastive support to be equally
        presented by the speakers in order to contrast the content of that support (e.g. in "the sun
        radiates its own light, but the moon reflects that of the sun"); in such cases, the
        contrasts are symmetrical in the sense that all their members are equally rhematic, and the
        contextualization of each of their members is reciprocated.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank" default="4"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:reciprocal"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="correspondingPhases" type="thesu:matchingPhases">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which a 'phase' or a range of 'repeatedPhases' in a
        'sequence' is contained either in a 'THESIS' connected by the annotator to another 'THESIS'
        in a relationship of entailment (via 'entailment' &#8594; 'entailedBy') or in 'PROPOSITION'
        connected to another 'PROPOSITION' in a relationship of entailment or similarity (via
        'relationships' &#8594; 'entailment' or 'relationships' &#8594; 'similarity'), and the thus
        referenced 'THESIS' or 'PROPOSITION' contains a 'sequence' referenced in a
        'correspondingThesisSequence' or 'correspondingPropositionSequence' child of the current
        'phase''s or 'repeatedPhases''s ancestor 'sequence'. This means that the current 'phase' or
        range of 'repeatedPhases' is contained in a 'sequence' taken by the annotator as entailed
        by, or similar in meaning to, another annotated 'sequence' (e.g. the sequence of the
        referenced 'THESIS' is "one must take the gray and make it red-yellow, and then immerse it
        in the white", and the sequence of the current 'THESIS', clarifying it, is "one must take
        the steel and bring it to red-yellow incandescence, and then immerse it in clean water"; or
        the sequence of the referenced 'PROPOSITION' is "the river flows into the sea after
        traversing rocky regions", and the sequence of the current 'PROPOSITION', logically entailed
        by the former, is "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater after having been
        in contact with rocks"). The current 'correspondingPhases' element is used to map each
        'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', via '@phasesRef', to the ones which correspond to them
        in the other 'sequence', i.e. the ones which entail them or are similar to them in meaning
        (e.g. the single phase "the river flows into the sea" would be corresponded by the other
        sequence's phase "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater"). Subtle
        divergences in the way the phases or range of phases are corresponded may be specified in a
        number or attributes. If the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' corresponds
        to only a part of the semantic content of the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases',
        which provide additional information independent from the former's message (e.g. if the
        phase "the river flows into the sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the river
        and the sewers flow into the sea", specify '@partial' as "true"); inversely, if the phase or
        range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' includes in its semantic content that of the
        current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' while also providing additional information
        independent from the latter's message (e.g. if the phase "the river and the sewers flow into
        the sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for 'the river flows into the sea"), specify
        '@extended' as "true"; if the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' is
        compatible in meaning with that of the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', but
        specifies it, in such a way as to be potentially encompassed by it (e.g. if the phase "the
        river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater" is referenced as a corresponding phase
        for "the river flows into the sea"), specify '@specified' as "true"; inversely, if the phase
        or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' is compatible in meaning with that of the
        current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', but generalizes it, in such a way as to
        potentially encompass it (e.g. if the phase "the river flows into the sea" is referenced as
        a corresponding phase for "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater"), specify
        '@generalized' as "true"; if the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef'
        corresponds in meaning to the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', but frames it in
        a quotation or report (e.g. if the phase "the fishermen know that the river flows into the
        sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the river flows into the sea"), specify
        '@quoted' as "true"; inversely, if the meaning of the phase or range of phases referenced in
        '@phasesRef', in the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', is framed in a quotation
        or report, and the reference implies its extraction from the quotation framing (e.g. if the
        phase "the river flows into the sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the
        fishermen know that the river flows into the sea"), specify '@extracted' as "true"; lastly,
        if the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' is similar in meaning to the
        current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', but diverges from it in some details (e.g. if
        the phase "the river flows into the lake" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the
        river flows into the sea"), specify '@altered' as "true". Note that all these attributes can
        be specified as "true" cumulatively (e.g. the phase "the fishermen know that the river's
        freshwater flows into the lake" can be referenced as a corresponding "quoted", "specified",
        and "altered" phase for "the river flows into the sea"). Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="correspondingPropositionSequence" type="thesu:matchingSequence">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>In the case a 'sequence''s ancestor 'PROPOSITION' has been connected to a
        corresponding 'PROPOSITION' in a relationship of similarity in meaning or entailment, via
        either 'relationships' &#8594; 'entailment' or 'relationships' &#8594; 'similarity', and
        that corresponding 'PROPOSITION' includes a 'sequence' whose content corresponds to that of
        the current 'sequence' due to similarity or entailment, the annotator may reference that
        'sequence' contained in the other 'PROPOSITION' via '@sequenceRef', in the form of an href
        to its ID. In this way, the current 'PROPOSITION''s 'sequence' will be mapped to its
        corresponding version in the other 'PROPOSITION'. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'. Note that each 'phase' in any of the current 'sequence''s descendant
        'phasesGroup' elements may also be individually linked to their corresponding versions in
        the other 'PROPOSITION' using the 'phase''s child element
        'correspondingPhases'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="correspondingThesisSequence" type="thesu:matchingSequence">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>In the case a 'sequence''s ancestor 'THESIS' has been connected via
        'entailment' &#8594; 'entailedBy' to a corresponding 'THESIS' (or 'SUPPORT' targeting a
        'THESIS'), taken by the annotator to entail or be faitfully reformulated by the current
        'THESIS', and that corresponding referenced 'THESIS' (or 'THESIS' targeted by the referenced
        'SUPPORT') includes a 'sequence' whose content corresponds to that of the current 'sequence'
        due to entailment or equivalence in meaning, the annotator may reference that 'sequence'
        contained in the other 'THESIS' via '@sequenceRef', in the form of an href to its ID. In
        this way, the current 'THESIS''s 'sequence' will be mapped to its corresponding version in
        the other 'THESIS'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'. Note that each
        'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' in any of the current 'sequence''s descendant
        'phasesGroup' elements may also be individually linked to their corresponding versions in
        the other 'THESIS' using the 'phase''s and 'repeatedPhases''s child element
        'correspondingPhases'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="customElement">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to include custom annotations in the TheSu document. This element
        can be provided freely with any attribute and child element.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:any minOccurs="0" processContents="lax"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:anyAttribute processContents="lax"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="deliberate">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, through '@value', whether an annotated 'metaphor' in a
        'THESIS' or 'MISC' corresponds to a metaphor or metonymy that has been deliberately used by
        its speakers or not (inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse it is included in).
        The annotator's choice may be supported, through 'proof', by referring to relevant textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source'). In the case the recognition of the speakers' intentionality is notably uncertain,
        '@uncertain' may be specified as "true". Since it can be open to debate, references to
        secondary literature may be added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:value"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="differences">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify that the spelling of the text that is referenced in this
        element's parent 'text' (as contained in the digital source whose URI is referred to in the
        attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') is taken to be partially or completely
        different for the purposes of the TheSu annotation, which assumes one or more divergent
        variant readings. These must be included in the same 'AEsystem' as 'lectio' elements and
        referenced under this element through 'lectioRef'. If only a segment of the variant reading
        is meant to substitute the text, use '@partialRef' to specify its extent.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:lectioRef" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:partialRef"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="durationAddition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="relativeEnd" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'relativeToPhases'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:relativeToPhases">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:choice>
                    <xs:element ref="thesu:fullyThemedTextRef"/>
                    <xs:element name="fullyThemedFreeText" type="thesu:fullyThemedFreeText">
                      <xs:annotation>
                        <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'fullyThemedFreeText'
                          complexType.</xs:documentation>
                      </xs:annotation>
                    </xs:element>
                  </xs:choice>
                  <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:eventParaphrasis"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:when"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:durationRange"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:timeUnit"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="employedElements">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to reference, via one or more 'elementRef' elements, all the
        'THESIS', 'MISC', and 'SUPPORT' elements, necessarily corresponding to parts of the
        discourse occurring in the text span indicated as 'text' for a 'SUPPORT', that are used by
        this same support to fulfill its functions (e.g. theses used as premises for argumentation).
        Additionally, if one or more employed elements have been omitted from the annotation, use an
        'omittedEmployedElements' element to record their types and number. For any SUPPORT, it is
        also allowed to omit the annotation of all employed elements, as long as an
        'omittedEmployedElements' element is used within them. The 'omittedEmployedElements' element
        may be left empty (without child elements) to indicate the presence of unspecified omissions
        without detailing their exact types.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="omittedEmployedElements" type="thesu:omissions" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'omissions' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="entailedBy">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>The ID of the 'PROPOSITION', 'THESIS', or 'SUPPORT' whose content entails
        that of this element's ancestor 'PROPOSITION' or 'THESIS' must be referenced via href in
        '@ref'. The annotator can specify the kind of entailment (e.g. inclusion or logical
        subalternity) by using '@entailedAs'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:entailedAs"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="entailment">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to connect a 'PROPOSITION' or 'THESIS' to other 'PROPOSITION',
        'THESIS', or 'SUPPORT' elements that logically entail it. Use an 'entailedBy' for each
        element with which the 'PROPOSITION' or 'THESIS' is in a relationship of
        entailment.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:entailedBy" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="exceptedPhases">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which a full range of phases referenced in
        'repeatedPhases' also includes 'phase' elements that are not relevant to the point of the
        sequence to which the same 'repeatedPhases' corresponds; that is, for the cases in which a
        discontinuous range of phases, previously annotated in a 'sequence', is re-employed at
        another point in the same or another 'sequence', with the new usage omitting one or more
        phases from the originally continuous range of phases. The whole range of phases that are
        skipped over at this new point, whether continuous or discontinuous, may be referenced in
        '@phasesRef'. It is also possible to specify whether the omission of the referenced excepted
        phases is explicitly communicated in the text corresponding to the current point of the
        sequence or only inferred by the annotator to be intended by the sequence's speakers or
        authors, and conveyed implicitly by their discourse: in the latter case, specify '@implicit'
        as "true". In either case, the annotator should prove that the sequence's speakers or
        authors intend such phases to be skipped over at the current point of the sequence via
        'proof', by referring to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the annotator's identification of the
        full range of omitted phases, along with the inference itself that phases are being skipped
        over at the current point of the sequence, can be open to debate, references to secondary
        literature may be added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Note that
        the value of '@implicit' and the referenced 'proof', as well as any scholarly reference,
        will be assumed to be related to the omission of each of the phases referenced in
        '@phasesRef'. If the full range of omitted phases includes explicitly omitted phases along
        with implicitly omitted phases, split the current 'exceptedPhases' into sibling elements,
        separately referencing the explicitly omitted phases and the implicitly omitted phases.
        Similarly split the 'exceptedPhases' element for specificities in the application of 'proof,
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra' to any sub-range of the total range of
        omitted phases.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="expansion">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, in '@rank', how prominent is the expansive function in a
        support with respects to the others, as indicated in the ranks of this element's siblings
        'argument', 'exposition', and 'contextualization'. If the chosen rank is higher than "4"
        &#8212;i.e. closer to "1"&#8212;, this means that the support is (also) used by its speakers
        as an excursus, i.e. to expand on the content of one or more 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT'
        elements favouring a more complete knowledge and understanding of it. To prove the
        prominence that has been indicated for this function, the annotator may use 'proof' and
        refer to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not
        corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this
        element's ancestor 'source') of the support's expansive function. Since the annotator's
        interpretation can be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank" default="4"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="exposition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, in '@rank', how prominent is the expository function in
        a support with respects to the others, as indicated in the ranks of this element's siblings
        'argument', 'expansion', and 'contextualization'. If the chosen rank is higher than "4"
        &#8212;i.e. closer to "1"&#8212;, this means that the support is (also) used by its speakers
        to explain more clearly, stylistically, or in depth the meaning of one or more 'THESIS',
        'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' elements. To prove the prominence that has been indicated for this
        function, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in
        a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to
        in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the support's expository
        function. Since the annotator's interpretation can be open to debate, it is also possible to
        add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank" default="4"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="fullyThemedTextRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via 'textRef', to one or more text segments in a digital
        source, while also specifying their broad or narrow themes in 'macroThemesGroup' or
        'microThemesGroup'. A 'macroThemesGroup' should be used when the annotator recognizes that
        the referenced text portion should be annotated with a different 'macroTheme' or hierarchy
        of 'macroTheme' elements than the one specified for this element's ancestor 'PROPOSITION' or
        'THESIS' in the 'propositionType''s or 'thesisType''s child 'macroThemesGroup'. A
        'microThemesGroup' should be used when the annotator recognizes that the referenced text
        portion should be annotated with a different set or focal arrangement of 'microTheme'
        elements than the one specified in the 'propositionType''s or 'thesisType''s child
        'microThemesGroup'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:textRef"/>
        <xs:element name="macroThemesGroup" type="thesu:macroThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'macroThemesGroup'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemesGroup">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element name="microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme'
                        complexType.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                    <xs:complexType>
                      <xs:complexContent>
                        <xs:restriction base="thesu:microTheme">
                          <xs:sequence>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
                            <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"
                              maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                          </xs:sequence>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
                        </xs:restriction>
                      </xs:complexContent>
                    </xs:complexType>
                  </xs:element>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:snippet" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="includedPropositions">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is the root element of an included document containing only
        'PROPOSITION' elements.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:PROPOSITION" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:base"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="includedRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer to a text passage that is referenced in the text of this
        element's ancestor 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT'. If the reference to such passage is not
        exlicit in the text, but only alluded to, '@implicit' must be specified as "true". The
        annotator may report the reference in various ways: either by providing links to a text span
        in a digital source, which can be done in 'locusRef', or by freely writing the coordinates
        of its locus, which can as well be done in 'locusRef', or by providing a link to a TheSu
        element that corresponds with it (if any), which can be done in 'elementRef'. To prove that
        the reference, in the text, does concern the passage that has been specified, the annotator
        may use 'proof' and point to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the indicated reference. Since the
        identification of the referenced passage can be open to debate, it is also possible to add
        references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:locusRef" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit" default="false"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="includedRefsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via one or more 'includedRef' elements, to text passages
        that are referenced in the text of a 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT'. In the case of 'THESIS'
        and 'MISC' elements, the references may be included here only if the passages that they
        refer to are not their objects, neither as objects of "metatextual" statements (as e.g. in
        the thesis, in a dialogue, "Glaucus's idea that the moon sends us heat like the sun is
        trivial", for which the details of the commented sentence would be provided in 'thesisType'
        &#8594; 'macroThemesGroup' &#8594; 'macroTheme' &#8594; 'metaTextDetails'), nor as objects
        of "historical" reports (as e.g. in the thesis, in a dialogue, "Glaucus has just claimed
        that the moon sends us heat like the sun", for which the details of the quotation would be
        provided in 'thesisType' &#8594; 'macroThemesGroup' &#8594; 'macroTheme' &#8594;
        'historyDetails'). To refer to such passages, the annotator may provide links to their
        corresponding text span in a digital source, the coordinates of their loci, or links to
        their corresponding TheSu elements (if any).</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:includedRef" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="interpretation">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify an interpretation of a metaphor or metonymy suggested or
        reported by the annotator, in the form of a paraphrasing tag or short designation
        translating the metaphor or metonymy in literal terms. In the case the metaphor or metonymy
        can be paraphrased as one or more keywords whose tags are present in the "keywordTags"
        authority record associated to the TheSu corpus, the annotator may reference these tags in
        one or more 'keywordTagRef' elements, possibly also specifying their narrow themes;
        otherwise, in the case the literalization can be hardly associated with any specific
        keyboard, the annotator may freely provide short paraphrasing designations in one or more
        'microThemedFreeText' as strings, while possibly also specifying their narrow themes. To
        prove that the specified interpretation can indeed capture the metaphor's or metonymy's
        intended meaning, the annotator may use 'proof' and refer to pertinent textual evidence
        (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source
        whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since
        the specified interpretation may be reported by the annotator without committing to it, and
        in any case be always open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary
        literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. If other possible
        interpretations of the same metaphor or metonymy are specified in this element's parent
        'interpretationsGroup', and the choice of the correct interpretation is recognized to be
        uncertain, the annotator may use '@rank' to specify how likely is each annotated
        'interpretation' to be the most likely to capture the metaphor's or metonymy's intended
        meaning, by giving it a value between "1" (most likely) and "4" (least likely). Custom
        elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:choice>
          <xs:element name="keywordTagRef" type="thesu:keywordTagRef" maxOccurs="unbounded">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'keywordTagRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
          </xs:element>
          <xs:element name="microThemedFreeText" maxOccurs="unbounded">
            <xs:annotation>
              <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemedFreeText'
                complexType.</xs:documentation>
            </xs:annotation>
            <xs:complexType>
              <xs:complexContent>
                <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemedFreeText">
                  <xs:sequence>
                    <xs:element name="freeText" type="thesu:freeText">
                      <xs:annotation>
                        <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a freely typed text in the form of a
                          string, either selected from a portion of the text corresponding to a
                          descendant element of a 'PROPOSITION' or "implicit" 'THESIS', as annotated
                          in these latter's 'paraphrasis', or unrelated to it. In the former case,
                          the annotator should ensure that the wording corresponds exactly to a text
                          span in the pertinent 'paraphrasis', and signal any points of
                          discontinuity in the quotation using '...'.</xs:documentation>
                      </xs:annotation>
                    </xs:element>
                    <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
                      <xs:annotation>
                        <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup'
                          complexType.</xs:documentation>
                      </xs:annotation>
                      <xs:complexType>
                        <xs:complexContent>
                          <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemesGroup">
                            <xs:sequence>
                              <xs:element name="microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
                                <xs:annotation>
                                  <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme'
                                    complexType.</xs:documentation>
                                </xs:annotation>
                                <xs:complexType>
                                  <xs:complexContent>
                                    <xs:restriction base="thesu:microTheme">
                                      <xs:sequence>
                                        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"
                                          maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                                      </xs:sequence>
                                      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
                                      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
                                    </xs:restriction>
                                  </xs:complexContent>
                                </xs:complexType>
                              </xs:element>
                            </xs:sequence>
                            <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
                          </xs:restriction>
                        </xs:complexContent>
                      </xs:complexType>
                    </xs:element>
                  </xs:sequence>
                  <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
                </xs:restriction>
              </xs:complexContent>
            </xs:complexType>
          </xs:element>
        </xs:choice>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank" default="1"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="interpretationsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify one or more interpretations of a metaphor or metonymy
        that the annotator may want to suggest or report, in the form of paraphrasing tags or short
        designations translating the metaphor or metonymy in literal terms (e.g. in the expression
        "the birth of rocks", the metaphorically used noun "birth" may be literalized as
        "formation"; in the expression "the sun dispenses the heat to its orbiting planets", the
        metaphorically used verb "to dispense... to" may be literalized as "originates... of"; in
        the expression "more hands were needed on the deck", the metonymically used noun "hand" may
        be literalized as "person" or "assistant"; etc.). The interpretations may either match or
        not match the interpretations of the metaphor or metonymy stated in the same discourse or
        macrotext by their own speakers (if present). Add an 'interpretation' for each suggested or
        reported interpretation of the metaphor or metonymy. If the correct interpretation is
        notably uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". In this case, if more than one
        interpretation is provided, the annotator must choose which of the interpretations are the
        most likely to capture the metaphor's or metonymy's intended meaning by attributing to them
        a higher rank, i.e. by specifying as e.g. "1" the '@rank' in their corresponding
        'interpretation' elements, and specifying as e.g. "2" that of the others. When multiple
        'interpretation' elements are provided with the same rank, it is assumed that the annotator
        understands all of their corresponding interpretations to be correct at the same time for
        the given metaphor or metonymy. In the case no 'interpretation' element is provided with
        rank "1", this means that the ambiguity is too high to reasonably propose a conclusive
        interpretation (but note that at least one interpretation, provided with rank "2", will
        still have to be favoured by the annotator). </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:interpretation" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="keyword">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a syntagm as a single keyword participating in the
        meaning one or more 'THESIS' or 'MISC' elements (and which could thus be referenced in a
        'keywordRef'); or, more simply, to annotate the narrow theme or semantic domain of a
        lexically meaningful syntagm (e.g. for the purposes of indexing) or to connect it to
        relevant secondary literature. Every 'keyword' must be given its own ID in '@xml:id', and
        associated with a span of the primary text which corresponds to the 'source' (i.e. the
        digital source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor
        'source') via 'text'. In the case of implicit keywords in the content of a 'THESIS' or
        'MISC' (e.g. entities alluded to by means of pronouns), the annotator must specify
        '@implicit' as "true", and reference in 'text' the complete text span corresponding to the
        'THESIS' and 'MISC' elements whose content implies them. In '@namely', the annotator may
        provide the keyword with one or more tags in order to allow it to be indexed along with its
        alternative spellings or forms encompassed by the same lexemes, annotating each tag in the
        form of an href to an authorized spelling contained in the keyword tags authority record
        associated with the TheSu document (i.e. whose URI is referred to in an 'authorityRecord'
        with '@keywordTags' specified as "true"). The keyword's narrow themes or semantic domains
        (e.g. "military", "psychological", etc.) may be specified in 'microThemesGroup'. The
        keyword's paraphrasis and association with micro-themes represents the annotator's
        interpretation of its corresponding segment of text: if the interpretation is notably
        uncertain, '@uncertain' may be specified as "true"; the interpretation may be supported,
        through 'proof', by referring to textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source,
        corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in the attribute
        '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') of the keyword's meaning or of its implicit
        presence. Since the interpretation can be open to debate, it is also possible to add
        references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. When a passage is ambiguous enough to allow for multiple interpretations,
        and thus for the annotation of more than one distinct, mutually exclusive 'keyword'
        elements, all of such keywords may be added to the TheSu document, but one of them will
        always have to be favoured by the annotator, and referred to by each of its alternative
        keywords in their respective 'alternativeTo' child elements. Custom elements can be added
        through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:text"/>
        <xs:element name="microThemesGroup">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemesGroup">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element name="microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme'
                        complexType.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                    <xs:complexType>
                      <xs:complexContent>
                        <xs:restriction base="thesu:microTheme">
                          <xs:sequence>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
                            <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"
                              maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                          </xs:sequence>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
                        </xs:restriction>
                      </xs:complexContent>
                    </xs:complexType>
                  </xs:element>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:alternativeTo" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:namely"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:doubleChecked"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="keywordSubRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer to one or more keywords of this element's ancestor 'THESIS'
        or 'PROPOSITION', inasmuch as they are referenced in its annotated 'keywordsGroup'. To
        select the keywords, specify in '@keywordsInSequence' the numbers of their corresponding
        'keywordRef' elements in their order of appearance in 'keywordsGroup'. The keyword's
        paraphrasis (in correspondence with that included in its '@namely', as an attribute of the
        original 'keyword' element and possibly also of the 'keywordRef') may be repeated here in
        '@namely', e.g. in order to make the annotation more easily readable for a
        human.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:keywordsInSequence"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:namely"/>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="lectio">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a variant reading of a segment of the primary text which
        corresponds to the 'source' (i.e. the digital source whose URI is referred to in the
        attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source') and deviates from the spelling
        reported in the "base edition" of its text (i.e. the edition, if any, whose URI is referred
        to in a 'bibliographyRef' with '@baseEdition' specified as "true"), i.e. to indicate that
        the spelling of a text segment in the digital source is different from the spelling of a
        corresponding text segment in another edition of the same text, or to report conjectural
        corrections of a segment of text. Every 'lectio' must be given its own ID in '@xml:id', and
        associated with a span of the primary text which corresponds to the 'source' via 'text', in
        correspondence with the exact segment of text that the variant reading, if accepted, would
        replace. The spelling of the variant reading must be reported in '@variant'. If the
        annotator, taking distance from the text of the source, decides to accept the annotated
        variant reading, '@accepted' may be specified as "true" (note that this will not eliminate
        the need of referring to this 'lectio' in the children elements 'differences' of all the
        'text' elements that assume it). The annotator may use 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra' to
        refer to secondary literature in which the acceptance of the annotated variant reading is
        supported or rejected; 'externalRef' can be used to refer to neutral comments and
        discussions on the subject. If the variant reading occurs in the indirect tradition of the
        text, '@indirectTrad' may be specified as "true"; if it is conjectural, '@conjectural' may
        be specified as "true"; if both of these attributes are specified as "false", it is assumed
        that the variant reading occurs in direct witnesses of the text. If the variant reading
        fills a gap in the text of the source, '@lacuna' may be specified as "true". Custom elements
        can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:text"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:variant" use="required"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:accepted" default="false"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:indirectTrad" default="false"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:conjectural" default="false"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:lacuna" default="false"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:doubleChecked"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="lectioRef" type="thesu:elementRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>The ID of the 'lectio' that includes the variant reading relevant to this
        element's ancestor 'text' must be referenced via href in '@ref'. Please refer to the
        'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="limitation">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the presence in the text of this element's ancestor
        'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' of a limitation to the speakers' full commitment towards its
        content at the time of their utterance. Its presence in the text should be proven, through
        'marker', by referencing text segments interpreted as discourse markers signalling the
        presence of such limitation. If this marker qualifies the 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' as
        weakened (e.g. "it is likely that...") specify '@weakened' as "true"; if as hyperbolic,
        specify '@hyperbolic' as "true"; if as humorous, specify '@humorous' as "true"; if as
        hypothetic and provisional, specify '@hypothetic' as "true"; if as fictitious, specify
        '@fictitious' as "true". Note that all the chosen values must be coherent with the discourse
        marker referenced in 'marker': if the text includes multiple distinct formulas expressing
        the limitations of the 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' cumulatively but independently, a
        corresponding 'limitation' element should be added for each of such formulas to the same
        'limitationsGroup'. If the interpretation of the formula expressing the limitation is
        notably uncertain, specify '@uncertain' as "true". Since the annotator's interpretation can
        be open to debate, it is also possible to add references to secondary literature, through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:marker" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:weakened"> </xs:attribute>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:hyperbolic"> </xs:attribute>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:humorous"> </xs:attribute>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:hypothetic"> </xs:attribute>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:fictitious"> </xs:attribute>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="limitationsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via one or more 'limitation' elements, the presence in
        the text of this element's parent 'THESIS', 'MISC', or 'SUPPORT' of any limitations to the
        speakers' full commitment towards it at the moment they speak or make the claim &#8212; i.e.
        signals that the 'THESIS' or 'SUPPORT' should be understood as a weakened claim (e.g. "it is
        likely that..."), as hyperbolic, as humorous, as hypothetic and provisional, or as
        fictitious (note that these limitations may be cumulative); or that the text span associated
        with a 'MISC' is generally of a weakened, hyperbolic, humorous, hypothetic and provisional,
        or fictitious character (note these characterizations may also be
        cumulative).</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:sequence>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:limitation" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
          </xs:sequence>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="locusFree">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide the coordinates of a referenced segment of text via a
        free-form, unlinked written reference. The reference must be specified in
        '@string'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:string"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="locusRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to provide the coordinates of a referenced segment of text, whether
        continuous or discontinuous. The annotator may either use one or more 'locusLink', to point
        to text segments in a digital source by means of an href to the URI of their starting and
        (if necessary) ending points, or specify the coordinates of the referenced passage in free
        form, i.e. as a human-readable locus reference, via 'locusFree'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="locusLink" type="thesu:segment" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'segment' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:locusFree" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:snippet" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="marker">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer to one or more text segments interpreted by the annotator
        as a unitary discourse marker, signalling that the information which corresponds directly to
        the parent element is present in the text's discourse (e.g., a 'SUPPORT' element may have a
        'marker' referencing the word "therefore", an 'analogy' may have a 'marker' referencing the
        words "just as", an 'etiology' may have a 'marker' referencing the words "because of", a
        'limitation' may have a 'marker' referencing the words "as a hypothesis", and a
        'metaphorRecognition' may have a 'marker' referencing the word "metaphorically"). The
        referenced text segments must be contained in the primary text corresponding to the 'source'
        (i.e. the digital source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's
        ancestor 'source'). To prove that the referenced text segments function as discourse markers
        for the annotated information, the annotator may use 'proof' and point to further textual
        evidence (i.e. text segments in a digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the
        source whose URI is referred to in the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source')
        justifying their interpretation. Since the interpretation can be open to debate, it is also
        possible to add references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. Custom elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:textRef" minOccurs="1"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="measureAddition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>To be defined soon. <!-- leftover --></xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="relativeTo" maxOccurs="unbounded" type="thesu:object"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:number"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:measurementUnit"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:measurementType"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:approximative"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:nonNumerical"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:where"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="matchingProposition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via '@propRef' in the form of an href, to a 'PROPOSITION'
        the annotator understands the 'THESIS' to be an instance of. The matching proposition does
        not have to be identical in meaning with the thesis, but must be similar enough to it to be
        connected with it usefully and representatively (e.g. the sentence "temperance has the first
        place, and humbleness the second" may be usefully connected to the proposition "temperance
        is more important than humbleness", although slightly different in meaning, if the context
        allows for the connection). It is also allowed to connect theses to propositions that only
        correspond to a part of them (e.g. the thesis "temperance and resolution benefit our
        intellect and well-being by removing superfluous distractions" to the proposition
        "temperance benefits our intellect"): in such cases, '@partial' must be specified as "true";
        inversely, theses can also be connected to propositions that include them while also
        providing additional information independent from the theses' message (e.g. the thesis
        "temperance benefits our intellect" to the proposition "temperance and resolution benefit
        our intellect and well-being by removing superfluous distractions"): in such cases,
        '@extended' must be specified as "true"; additionally, theses can be connected to
        propositions which are compatible in meaning with the theses, but specify them in such a way
        as to be potentially encompassed by them (e.g. the thesis "temperance benefits our
        intellect" to the proposition "the virtue of temperance usually benefits our intellect by
        removing superfluous distractions"): in such cases, '@specified' must be specified as
        "true"; inversely, theses can also be connected to propositions which are compatible in
        meaning with the theses, but generalize them in such a way as to potentially encompass them
        (e.g. the thesis "temperance benefits our intellect" to the proposition "certain virtues can
        benefit our mind"): in such cases, '@generalized' must be specified as "true"; furthermore,
        theses may be connected with propositions that do not match them directly, but frame them in
        quotations or reports (e.g. the thesis "temperance benefits our intellect" to the
        proposition "Aristotle said that temperance benefits our intellect"): in such cases,
        '@quoted' must be specified as "true"; inversely, quotations or reports of sentences may be
        connected directly with the propositions that match these sentences (rather than matching
        the quotations themselves), thereby extracting the quoted thesis from the quotation or
        report that frames it (e.g. the thesis "Aristotle said that temperance benefits our
        intellect" to the proposition "temperance benefits our intellect"): in such cases,
        '@extracted' must be specified as "true"; lastly, theses can be connected to propositions
        which are similar in meaning with the theses, but diverge from them in some details (e.g.
        the thesis "temperance benefits our intellect" to the proposition "discipline and
        orderliness benefit our intellect"): in such cases, '@altered' must be specified as "true".
        All these attributes can be specified as "true" cumulatively (e.g. in the case of the thesis
        "Aristotle said that temperance benefits our intellect by removing superfluous distractions"
        towards the "extended", "extracted", and "altered" proposition "temperance and resolution
        benefit our intellect and well-being by removing all distractions").</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:propRef" use="required"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:differencesInCorrespondence"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="matchingPropositionPhases" type="thesu:matchingPhases">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which a 'phase' or a range of 'repeatedPhases' in a
        'sequence' is contained in a 'THESIS' connected by the annotator either to another 'THESIS'
        in a relationship of entailment (via 'entailment' &#8594; 'entailedBy') or to another
        'PROPOSITION' in a relationship of entailment or similarity (via 'relationships' &#8594;
        'entailment' or 'relationships' &#8594; 'similarity'), and the thus referenced 'THESIS' or
        'PROPOSITION' contains a 'sequence' referenced in a 'correspondingThesisSequence' or
        'correspondingPropositionSequence' child of the current 'phase''s or 'repeatedPhases''s
        ancestor 'sequence'. This means that the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' is
        contained in a 'sequence' taken by the annotator as entailed by, or similar in meaning to,
        another annotated 'sequence' (e.g. the sequence of the referenced 'THESIS' is "one must take
        the gray and make it red-yellow, and then immerse it in the white", and the sequence of the
        current 'THESIS', clarifying it, is "one must take the steel and bring it to red-yellow
        incandescence, and then immerse it in clean water"; or the sequence of the referenced
        'PROPOSITION' is "the river flows into the sea after traversing rocky regions", and the
        sequence of the current 'PROPOSITION', logically entailed by the former, is "the river's
        freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater after having been in contact with rocks"). The
        current 'correspondingPhases' element is used to map each 'phase' or range of
        'repeatedPhases', via '@phasesRef', to the ones which correspond to them in the other
        'sequence', i.e. the ones which entail them or are similar to them in meaning (e.g. the
        single phase "the river flows into the sea" would be corresponded by the other sequence's
        phase "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater"). Subtle divergences in the
        way the phases or range of phases are corresponded may be specified in a number or
        attributes. If the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' corresponds to only a
        part of the semantic content of the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', which
        provide additional information independent from the former's message (e.g. if the phase "the
        river flows into the sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the river and the
        sewers flow into the sea", specify '@partial' as "true"); inversely, if the phase or range
        of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' includes in its semantic content that of the current
        'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' while also providing additional information independent
        from the latter's message (e.g. if the phase "the river and the sewers flow into the sea" is
        referenced as a corresponding phase for 'the river flows into the sea"), specify '@extended'
        as "true"; if the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' is compatible in
        meaning with that of the current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', but specifies it, in
        such a way as to be potentially encompassed by it (e.g. if the phase "the river's freshwater
        encounters the sea's saltwater" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the river flows
        into the sea"), specify '@specified' as "true"; inversely, if the phase or range of phases
        referenced in '@phasesRef' is compatible in meaning with that of the current 'phase' or
        range of 'repeatedPhases', but generalizes it, in such a way as to potentially encompass it
        (e.g. if the phase "the river flows into the sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for
        "the river's freshwater encounters the sea's saltwater"), specify '@generalized' as "true";
        if the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef' corresponds in meaning to the
        current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', but frames it in a quotation or report (e.g.
        if the phase "the fishermen know that the river flows into the sea" is referenced as a
        corresponding phase for "the river flows into the sea"), specify '@quoted' as "true";
        inversely, if the meaning of the phase or range of phases referenced in '@phasesRef', in the
        current 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases', is framed in a quotation or report, and the
        reference implies its extraction from the quotation framing (e.g. if the phase "the river
        flows into the sea" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the fishermen know that the
        river flows into the sea"), specify '@extracted' as "true"; lastly, if the phase or range of
        phases referenced in '@phasesRef' is similar in meaning to the current 'phase' or range of
        'repeatedPhases', but diverges from it in some details (e.g. if the phase "the river flows
        into the lake" is referenced as a corresponding phase for "the river flows into the sea"),
        specify '@altered' as "true". Note that all these attributes can be specified as "true"
        cumulatively (e.g. the phase "the fishermen know that the river's freshwater flows into the
        lake" can be referenced as a corresponding "quoted", "specified", and "altered" phase for
        "the river flows into the sea"). Remember that when a sequence contains multiple
        'matchingPropositionSequence' elements (as siblings), and phases within this sequence
        contain multiple 'matchingPropositionPhases' elements, a positional mapping is assumed to be
        maintained between them. The first 'matchingPropositionPhases' element is mapped to the
        first 'matchingPropositionSequence', the second to the second, and so on. Custom elements
        can be added through 'customElement'. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="matchingPropositionSequence" type="thesu:matchingSequence">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>In the case a 'sequence''s ancestor 'THESIS' has been connected to a
        corresponding 'PROPOSITION' via 'matchingPropositionsGroup' &#8594; 'matchingProposition',
        and that corresponding 'PROPOSITION' includes a 'sequence' matching the current sequence in
        propositional terms, the annotator may reference that 'sequence' contained in the
        'PROPOSITION' via '@sequenceRef', in the form of an href to its ID. In this way, the current
        'THESIS''s 'sequence' will be mapped to its propositional version. Remember that when
        multiple 'matchingPropositionSequence' elements are present as siblings within the same
        'sequence', their ordinal position is significant. It is assumed that a consistent
        first-to-first, second-to-second (etc.) mapping holds between these elements and any
        'matchingPropositionPhases' elements in the descendant phases. That is, the first
        'matchingPropositionPhases' in a phase maps to the first sequence in
        'matchingPropositionSequence', the second to the second, and so on. This ordered
        correspondence must be maintained for proper semantic interpretation. Custom elements can be
        added through 'customElement'. Note that each 'phase' or range of 'repeatedPhases' in any of
        the current 'sequence''s descendant 'phasesGroup' elements may also be individually linked
        to their propositional versions using the 'phase''s and 'repeatedPhases''s child element
        'matchingPropositionPhases'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="matchingPropositionsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via one or more 'matchingProposition' elements, to the
        abstract propositions the annotator understands the 'THESIS' to be an instance of, to
        connect it indirectly with all the theses that appear to be synonymous (enough) with it. The
        matching 'PROPOSITION' elements are not necessarily identical in meaning with the thesis,
        but are similar enough to it to be connected with it usefully and representatively (e.g. the
        sentence "temperance has the first place, and humbleness the second" may be usefully
        connected to the proposition "temperance is more important than humbleness", although
        slightly different in meaning, if the context allows for the connection: in a different
        context, it may be rather connected to e.g. "temperance is more rewarded than humbleness";
        in this sense, also the association of a thesis with a matching proposition reflects the
        annotator's interpretation of the text); it is also allowed to connect theses to
        propositions that only correspond to a part of them or to propositions that include them
        while also providing additional information, and quotations of sentences may be connected
        directly with the propositions that match these sentences (rather than matching the
        quotations themselves, which are "historical" reports); each of such cases of imperfect
        matching is signalled via attributes in 'matchingProposition'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:matchingProposition" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="maySubstitute">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is for the cases in which the annotator interprets a sequence contained
        in a 'THESIS', inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse or macrotext this is
        included in, to be intended by its own speakers or authors as a variant, diverging account
        of another description (or part of another description) of the same process, or as an
        alternative, diverging procedure of a set of instructions (or part of a set of instructions)
        for the same purpose (or a similar one). The other 'sequence' of which the current
        'sequence' is interpreted to be a variant of may be referenced via '@sequenceRef', in the
        form of an href to its ID. In absence of further specifications, it is assumed that the
        current 'sequence' is interpreted to be a variant of the referenced 'sequence' as a whole,
        and that its phases are intended to substitute all the phases of the other sequence (note
        that this does not exclude the possibility of the current sequence re-employing any number
        of phases of the original sequence, as ranges of re-employed phases may still be referenced
        in any 'phasesGroup' elements containted in the current 'sequence', through their child
        element 'repeatedPhases'). If the current sequence is interpreted to be a variant of only a
        sub-range &#8212; whether continuous or discontinuous &#8212; of the phases of the
        referenced original 'sequence', the annotator must also use '@phasesRef' to reference all
        the ranges of 'phasesGroup' children of the same 'sequence', along with their 'phase'
        descendants, which are intended to be substituted by the current variant. Once the full
        range of phases of which the current sequence is interpreted to be a variant of has been
        referenced via '@sequenceRef' and '@phasesRef', it is also possible to specify whether the
        role of variant attributed to the current sequence, along with its connection to the
        indicated original sequence or range of phases, is explicitly communicated in the text
        corresponding to the current sequence or only inferred by the annotator to be intended by
        the sequence's speakers or authors, and conveyed implicitly by their discourse: in the
        latter case, specify '@implicit' as "true". In either case, the annotator should prove that
        the current sequence's speakers or authors intend it to be a variant of another sequence or
        range of phases, and to be a variant preceisely of the referenced sequence or range of
        phases, via 'proof', by referring to pertinent textual evidence (i.e. text segments in a
        digital source, corresponding or not corresponding to the source whose URI is referred to in
        the attribute '@ref' of this element's ancestor 'source'). Since the annotator's
        identification of the full range of phases intended to be substituted by the current
        variant, along with the inference itself that the current sequence is intended by its own
        speakers or authors as a variant, can be open to debate, references to secondary literature
        may be added through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'. Custom elements can
        be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:sequenceRef"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:phasesRef"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:implicit"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphor">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate details on the structure, meaning, and status (in
        relation to the awareness of its speakers) of a metaphor or metonymy included in the text of
        a 'THESIS' or 'MISC', as well as the annotator's suggested or reported interpretations of
        it. The metaphorically or metonymically used term &#8212;i.e. the figure, vehicle, or
        source&#8212; must be referenced in 'metaphorComponentsGroup'. In 'metaphorComponentsGroup',
        it is also possible to indicate the recipient, in the text, of the metaphorically or
        metonymically conveyed idea &#8212;i.e. the tenor or target&#8212;, and the meaning of the
        metaphor or metonymy, in the case this is literalized in any place of the same discourse or
        macrotext. If the term's metaphorical or metonymic character is notably uncertain, specify
        '@uncertain' as "true". Since this can be open to debate, it is also possible to add
        references to secondary literature, through 'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and
        'scholarContra'. The annotated metaphors or metonymies may be judged &#8212;on the basis of
        the full discourses they are included in&#8212; to be sometimes unconscious to their
        speakers, who take them literally (e.g. when only the annotator recognizes them to be
        metaphors, as in the case of some cognitive metaphors), and other times to be conscious; and
        sometimes unintentional (whether also unconscious or not, as in the case of most catachreses
        and lexicalized metaphors) and others deliberate; and sometimes meant to be ditropically
        ambiguous, i.e. activating their metaphorical or metonymic sense (with respects to the same
        'THESIS' or 'MISC') simultaneously with their literal meaning, and others to be univocally
        metaphors or metonymies. All of these cases can be specified and proven in
        'metaphorConsciousness'. If specific speakers, in the text, appear to recognize or interpret
        the annotated metaphor or metonymy to be a metaphor or metonymy (as e.g. in explicit
        declarations of figurative speaking, or in allegorical interpretations of sentences that
        might have been literal in origin), the annotator may specify their names or group
        designators in 'metaphorRecognitionsGroup', and refer to the text spans corresponding to
        their comments on the metaphor or metonymy. In the case such text span includes the terms
        that have been annotated as the metaphor or metonymy's meaning in 'metaphorComponentsGroup',
        it is assumed that this meaning is only attributed to the metaphor or metonymy by the
        speakers associated with this text span. In any case, since metaphors and metonymies can
        always be the object of comments or explanations in the text that the annotator may want to
        include in the TheSu document as (e.g.) "metatextual" THESIS elements or "expository"
        SUPPORT elements, every 'metaphor' can also be provided with its own ID, to use it as a
        target for references in other elements. The annotator's suggested or reported
        interpretations of the metaphor or metonymy, inasmuch as it is possible to literalize it in
        paraphrasing tags or short designations, can be specified in 'interpretationsGroup'. Custom
        elements can be added through 'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphorComponentsGroup"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphorConsciousness" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphorRecognitionsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:interpretationsGroup" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:id"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:metonymy" default="false"/>
      <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphorComponent">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a textual component of a metaphor or metonymy occurring
        in a 'THESIS' or 'MISC'. Its text may be specified in three ways: by referring, via
        'keywordSubRef', to one or more of the keywords that have been annotated for the 'THESIS' or
        'MISC' in its descendant 'keywordsGroup'; by referring, via 'microThemedTextRef', to the
        exact segments of text that correspond to the component while also providing them with their
        own (micro-)thematic annotation (which is useful when the annotator has decided not to
        annotate the component as one or more 'keyword' elements, but wants to indicate its most
        relevant narrow themes in the same way as would be done for 'keyword' elements); or by
        freely typing in, in 'microThemedFreeText', the span of text corresponding to the component
        as it is specified in the 'paraphrasis' of the 'THESIS' or 'MISC' while also providing it
        with its own micro-thematic annotation (which is useful when the component corresponds to
        implicit text which the annotator has decided not to annotate as one or more 'keyword'
        elements, but wants to indicate its most relevant narrow themes in the same way as would be
        done for 'keyword' elements). The component's role in the metaphor or metonymy must be
        specified in '@role' by using one of the following values: "vehicle" if it is the
        metaphorically or metonymically used term; "tenor" if it is the recipient, in the text, of
        the metaphorically or metonymically conveyed idea; and "meaning" if it is the meaning of the
        metaphor or metonymy, literalized in a text. If the metaphor component corresponds to words
        denoting or implying an action, and thus their subject's ability to be an agent (e.g.
        "employs", "operation", etc.), '@agency' may be specified as "true"; if the corresponding
        words are best understood when their subject is a human or any other intelligent being (e.g.
        "thinks", "dishonest", etc.), '@personhood' may be specified as true. In this way, animistic
        and anthropomorphic terminology will be indexed independently of the chosen
        micro-themes.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:choice>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:keywordSubRef"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:microThemedTextRef"/>
        <xs:element name="microThemedFreeText">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemedFreeText'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemedFreeText">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element name="freeText" type="thesu:freeText">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a freely typed text in the form of a
                        string, either selected from a portion of the text corresponding to a
                        descendant element of a 'PROPOSITION' or "implicit" 'THESIS', as annotated
                        in these latter's 'paraphrasis', or unrelated to it. In the former case, the
                        annotator should ensure that the wording corresponds exactly to a text span
                        in the pertinent 'paraphrasis', and signal any points of discontinuity in
                        the quotation using '...'.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                  </xs:element>
                  <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup'
                        complexType.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                    <xs:complexType>
                      <xs:complexContent>
                        <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemesGroup">
                          <xs:sequence>
                            <xs:element name="microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
                              <xs:annotation>
                                <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme'
                                  complexType.</xs:documentation>
                              </xs:annotation>
                              <xs:complexType>
                                <xs:complexContent>
                                  <xs:restriction base="thesu:microTheme">
                                    <xs:sequence>
                                      <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
                                      <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
                                      <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"
                                        maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                                    </xs:sequence>
                                    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
                                    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
                                    <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
                                  </xs:restriction>
                                </xs:complexContent>
                              </xs:complexType>
                            </xs:element>
                          </xs:sequence>
                          <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
                        </xs:restriction>
                      </xs:complexContent>
                    </xs:complexType>
                  </xs:element>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
      </xs:choice>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:role" default="vehicle"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:agency"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:personhood"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphorComponentsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify the textual components of a metaphor or metonymy
        occurring in a 'THESIS' or 'MISC', which are: the metaphorically or metonymically used term
        &#8212; i.e. the figure, vehicle, or source; the recipient, in the text, of the
        metaphorically or metonymically conveyed idea &#8212; i.e. the tenor or target; and the
        meaning of the metaphor or metonymy, if literalized in any place of the same discourse or
        macrotext. At least one 'metaphorComponent' must be added, to specify the vehicle of the
        metaphor or metonymy.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphorComponent" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphorConsciousness">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, in 'conscious', whether the speakers of a 'THESIS' or
        'MISC' &#8212;inasmuch as can be inferred from the full discourse this is included in&#8212;
        are aware of the metaphoric or metonymic character of an expression they have used in it or
        not (as sometimes it may be taken literally by the speakers, as e.g. in the case of certain
        cognitive metaphors which are only recognized to be such by the annotator); in 'deliberate',
        whether this metaphor or metonymy is deliberately used by the speakers or not (as
        catachreses and lexicalized metaphors are often not); in 'ambiguous', whether this is meant
        to be ditropically ambiguous &#8212;i.e. activating its metaphorical or metonymic sense
        (with respects to the same 'THESIS' or 'MISC') simultaneously with its literal
        meaning&#8212; or univocally a metaphor or metonymy. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:deliberate"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:ambiguous"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphorRecognition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, in 'speakersGroup', the names or group designators of
        one or more speakers that, in a text, appear to recognize or interpret together an annotated
        'metaphor' as a metaphor or metonymy (as e.g. in explicit declarations of figurative
        speaking, or in allegorical interpretations of sentences that might have even been literal
        in origin); and to reference, via 'marker', the text segments interpreted by the annotator
        as discourse markers signalling the speakers' framing of the 'metaphor' as a metaphor or
        metonymy (e.g. the words "metaphorically", or "in this allegory", etc.).</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="speakersGroup" type="thesu:speakersGroup">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'speakersGroup' complexType. Consider the parent
              'metaphorRecognition' as if it were a statement on the metaphorical or metonymic
              character of the annotated 'metaphor'.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:marker" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphorRecognitionsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to specify, via one or more 'metaphorRecognition' elements, the
        names or group designators of all the speakers that appear, in a text, to recognize or
        interpret an annotated 'metaphor' to be a metaphor or metonymy (as e.g. in explicit
        declarations of figurative speaking, or in allegorical interpretations of sentences that
        might have been literal in origin); and to refer to the text spans corresponding to their
        comments on the metaphor or metonymy.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphorRecognition" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="metaphorsGroup">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate details on the structure, meaning, and status of any
        metaphor or metonymy included in the text of this element's ancestor 'THESIS' or 'MISC'. Add
        a 'metaphor' for each distinct metaphor or metonymy in the text.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:metaphor" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="microThemedTextRef">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer, via 'textRef', to one or more text segments in a digital
        source, while also specifying their narrow themes in 'microThemesGroup', in the same way as
        would be done for a 'keyword'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:textRef"/>
        <xs:element name="microThemesGroup" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microThemesGroup'
              complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
          <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
              <xs:restriction base="thesu:microThemesGroup">
                <xs:sequence>
                  <xs:element name="microTheme" maxOccurs="unbounded">
                    <xs:annotation>
                      <xs:documentation>Please, refer to the 'microTheme'
                        complexType.</xs:documentation>
                    </xs:annotation>
                    <xs:complexType>
                      <xs:complexContent>
                        <xs:restriction base="thesu:microTheme">
                          <xs:sequence>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:conscious" minOccurs="0"/>
                            <xs:group ref="thesu:proofBundle"/>
                            <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0"
                              maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
                          </xs:sequence>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:microThemeTag" use="required"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:focus" default="1"/>
                          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:rank"/>
                        </xs:restriction>
                      </xs:complexContent>
                    </xs:complexType>
                  </xs:element>
                </xs:sequence>
                <xs:attributeGroup ref="thesu:uncertainWithComment"/>
              </xs:restriction>
            </xs:complexContent>
          </xs:complexType>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:snippet" minOccurs="0"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="newPropositions">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate new 'PROPOSITION' elements to be referred to in the
        'matchingProposition' elements of the same corpus.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:PROPOSITION" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="xml:base"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="omittedMISCS" type="thesu:omittedElements">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to indicate that one or more MISC discourse components relevant to
        this element's ancestor 'targetsGroup' or 'employedElements' were omitted from the
        annotation. The '@number' attribute may be used to specify the exact quantity of omitted
        elements, including when only a single element is omitted (by setting '@number="1"'). If the
        '@number' attribute is not provided, the quantity is considered unspecified, indicating that
        one or more elements may have been omitted without committing to an exact
        count.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="omittedSUPPORTS">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to indicate that one or more SUPPORT elements relevant to this
        element's ancestor 'targetsGroup' or 'employedElements' were omitted from the annotation.
        When multiple SUPPORT elements with the same function are omitted (e.g., two separate
        arguments in support of the same thesis), they must be grouped under a single
        'omittedSUPPORTS' element. If omitted supports serve different functions, each must be
        recorded in a separate 'omittedSUPPORTS' element. The '@number' attribute may be used to
        specify the exact quantity of omitted supports with the same function, including when only a
        single support is omitted (by setting '@number="1"'). If the '@number' attribute is not
        provided, the quantity is considered unspecified, indicating that one or more supports may
        have been omitted without committing to an exact count. The annotator may explicitly record
        the functions that the omitted supports were meant to serve — namely, argumentation,
        exposition, expansion, and/or contextualization — by specifying their relative prominence
        through the associated '@omitted*Rank' attributes. A value of "1" indicates the highest
        prominence and "4" indicates no particular relevance. For further details on the logic and
        rationale of the functions' ranking, please refer to the 'supportFunctionsGroup'
        element.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:extension base="thesu:omittedElements">
          <xs:sequence>
            <xs:element ref="thesu:omittedSupportsFunctions"/>
          </xs:sequence>
        </xs:extension>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="omittedSupportsFunctions">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This can be used to rank the respective prominence of the functions in an
        omitted SUPPORT element. It can record the intended prominence of each function —
        argumentation, exposition, expansion, and contextualization — via the corresponding
        '@omitted*Rank' attributes. The numerical values follow the same scale as for SUPPORTS that
        are not omitted in the annotation, where "1" indicates the highest prominence and "4"
        indicates no specific relevance. For further details on the logic and rationale of the
        functions' ranking, please refer to the 'supportFunctionsGroup' element. </xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:complexContent>
        <xs:restriction base="xs:anyType">
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:omittedArgumentationRank"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:omittedExpositionRank"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:omittedExpansionRank"/>
          <xs:attribute ref="thesu:omittedContextualisationRank"/>
        </xs:restriction>
      </xs:complexContent>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="omittedTHESES" type="thesu:omittedElements">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to indicate that one or more THESIS elements relevant to this
        element's ancestor 'targetsGroup' or 'employedElements' were omitted from the annotation.
        The '@number' attribute may be used to specify the exact quantity of omitted elements,
        including when only a single thesis is omitted (by setting '@number="1"'). If the '@number'
        attribute is not provided, the quantity is considered unspecified, indicating that one or
        more theses may have been omitted without committing to an exact count.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="opposedTo">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>The ID of the 'PROPOSITION' that is opposed to this element's ancestor
        'PROPOSITION' must be referenced via href in '@ref'. The annotator can specify the kind of
        opposition (e.g. contrariety or contradiction) by using '@opposedAs'. Since the recognized
        opposition can be open to debate, references to secondary literature may be added through
        'externalRef', 'scholarPro', and 'scholarContra'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:group ref="thesu:scholarshipBundle"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:ref"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:opposedAs"/>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="opposition">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to connect the 'PROPOSITION' to others that are opposed to it. The
        annotator can specify the kind of opposition (e.g. ) by using '@entailedAs'. Use an
        'opposedTo' element for each.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:opposedTo" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="proof">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to refer to textual evidence supporting one or more details of the
        annotation in the parent element. Specification of the relevant detail can be included in
        '@comment' as a free text string. The annotator may include the reference to supporting
        evidence in various way: either by providing links to a text span in a digital source, which
        can be done in 'locusRef', or by freely writing the coordinates of its locus, which can as
        well be done in 'locusRef', or by providing a link to a TheSu element that corresponds with
        it (if any), which can be done in 'elementRef'. Custom elements can be added through
        'customElement'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:locusRef" minOccurs="0"/>
        <xs:element name="elementRef" type="thesu:elementRef" minOccurs="0">
          <xs:annotation>
            <xs:documentation>Please refer to the 'elementRef' complexType.</xs:documentation>
          </xs:annotation>
        </xs:element>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:customElement" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
      </xs:sequence>
      <xs:attribute ref="thesu:comment"/>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="propositions">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to contain all the 'PROPOSITION' elements that are referred to in
        the 'matchingProposition' elements in the corpus: to include a separate document containing
        only 'PROPOSITION' elements, refer an element 'xi:include' to a document with
        'includedPropositions' as root element; to annotate new 'PROPOSITION' elements use
        'newPropositions'.</xs:documentation>
    </xs:annotation>
    <xs:complexType>
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:includedPropositions" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
        <xs:element ref="thesu:newPropositions"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:complexType>
  </xs:element>

  <xs:element name="propositionType">
    <xs:annotation>
      <xs:documentation>This is to annotate a 'PROPOSITION' thematically and specify some of its
        formal features. The proposition's broad theme (e.g. "historical", "axiological", etc.) can
        be specified in 'macroThemesGroup'; to specify the theme in more detail (e.g. "military",
        "psychological", etc.) 'microThemesGroup' may be used. Each of the words composing the
        proposition's text &#8212;in correspondence with that included in this element's sibling
        'paraphrasis'&#8212; can be annotated as a keyword directly (i.e. without referring to a
        'keyword' that has been annotated in the same 'source', as is necessary in 'THESIS' and
        'MISC' elements) in 'keywordsGroup'. If the proposition has the structure of a definition,
        this may be specified in 'definition'. If the proposition includes descriptions of chains of
        events (at least two, e.g. "the river flows into the sea after traversing rocky regions"),
        reported or prescribed procedures (including recipes, e.g. "to harden steel, one must first
        bring it to incandescence and then immerse it in a cold liquid"), or a mix of the two (e.g.
        "to harden steel, one must heat it first; in the fire, it eventually becomes red-yellow:
        when this happens, one must immerse it in a cold liquid"), these processes may be analyzed
        in their phases in 'sequencesGroup', along with details on each phase (involved objects or
        ingredients, duration, etc.). If the proposition includes etiologies (i.e. reports of the
        causes or ends of one or more events), their structure may be annotated in
        'etiologiesGroup'. If the proposition includes analogies or comparisons, their structure may
